Police said the 71 - year - old was one of three men walking on Kells Avenue at about 08:25 BST . A red car stopped beside the group. A man, described as being in his 30s with dark hair, emerged from the passenger side of the vehicle. He brandished what appeared to be a knife and aggressively demanded that the men hand over their possessions. The 71-year-old, along with the other two men, complied with the demands, fearing for their safety. The assailant quickly snatched a wallet and a mobile phone from the group before re-entering the red car, which then sped off in the direction of the town centre. Police were immediately alerted to the incident. Officers arrived within minutes and cordoned off the area to begin their investigation. Initial inquiries suggest the vehicle was a red Toyota hatchback, though full details are still emerging. Detectives are now reviewing CCTV footage from nearby properties and appealing to anyone who witnessed the incident, or saw a red car acting suspiciously in the area around that time, to contact them. The victims, although shaken, did not sustain any physical injuries.

Lincolnshire Police is taking on about 150 officers over the next two years . The force is restricting applications to people who have lived in the county for at least the past 12 months . The county 's Police and Crime Commissioner , Marc Jones , said the advert had attracted a phenomenal response from high-calibre individuals. He highlighted that the policy of limiting applications to those with a recent connection to Lincolnshire was a deliberate strategy to recruit officers who genuinely understand and are invested in their local communities. "It's crucial that our officers not only reflect the diverse population of Lincolnshire but also possess a deep understanding of its unique challenges and characteristics," Mr Jones explained. "Officers who live here are intrinsically motivated to make Lincolnshire a safer place. They know the streets, the people, and the specific issues that matter most to our residents."

This proactive measure by Lincolnshire Police aims to foster stronger community ties and enhance local policing effectiveness. The residency requirement ensures that new recruits have an established connection to the area, which can lead to greater trust and more effective problem-solving within neighborhoods. While Chief Constable Neil Rhodes retired some years ago, the sentiment of officers being embedded within their communities, as he often advocated, remains a core tenet for Lincolnshire Police. The force believes this local approach will significantly benefit public confidence and visible policing across the entire county. The recruitment drive is a cornerstone of the Police and Crime Plan, designed to deliver a dedicated, locally-rooted police service for Lincolnshire for years to come.

The Arsenal FC midfielder, 24, uploaded a picture from his 2014 wedding with the caption "un flwyddyn heddiw", which means "one year [ago] today".
In contrast to positive responses, some users expressed confusion while others ridiculed the message.
One questioned whether the FA Cup winner was "drunk" and another asked if he had "had a seizure".
The tweet, posted on 8 June, attracted criticism for its lack of an English translation.
Twitter user @RightJudgeIam posted: "Did you lean on the keyboard?"
While @BanterousGooner said: "Did you have a seizure while typing this or something?"
Arsenal fan @MegatronAFC, who describes herself as an "Aaron Ramsey enthusiast", said: "I didn't know Welsh was a language lol [sic]."
Many of the tweets have since been deleted and people rushed to support Mr Ramsey on the micro-blogging site, calling the negative posts "horrible".
Andrea Williams, from Rhymney, Caerphilly county, using her twitter handle @tyclyd1972, posted: "Why put such horrible status don't be jealous cause we got a different language we r proud to talk Welsh [sic]."
"Good to see people like @AaronRamsey tweeting in Welsh," Ffion Elena posted. "Can only be positive for our language."
Mr Ramsey, who was raised in Caerphilly, attended Welsh-medium school Ysgol Gyfun Cwm Rhymni before signing with Cardiff City's youth academy.
He played in Wales' crucial 1-0 home win against Belgium on Friday and has scored nine times during his 34 appearances for his country.

Kelly Hewitt , 41 , was found by the side of the A66 on Teesside in March 2014 with severe injuries to her head and body, consistent with being hit by a vehicle. Despite the efforts of paramedics and hospital staff, she tragically died later that day at James Cook University Hospital in Middlesbrough. An extensive police investigation was launched, which ultimately led to the identification of Clare Bailey, the driver of a stolen car, as the person responsible. Bailey, then 26 and also from Middlesbrough, was subsequently convicted of causing death by dangerous driving and jailed, bringing some closure to Kelly's devastated family and the Teesside community.

American Troy Bradley and Russian Leonid Tiukhtyaev landed safely, their Two Eagles Balloon team said.
They claim to have beaten the world distance and duration records by flying for more than 137 hours and travelling more than 5,209 miles (8,383km).
To set the records the team needed to beat the existing records by 1%.
"The Two Eagles balloon team is pleased to report the Two Eagles balloon has landed safely just off the Baja coast near La Poza Grande," their team said in a statement.
"The pilots made a controlled descent to a gentle water landing about four miles off the Baja coast. The balloon is stable and still inflated and the pilots are fine."
The two pilots left Japan on Sunday and had aimed to land in Canada or the US. However, weather forced them to change course towards Mexico.
They were met in the sea by a Mexican fishing boat.
The statement stressed that the sea landing was acceptable "under the international rules governing the establishment of world records".
"Two around-the-world attempts using a different type of balloon landed in the water and were approved as records."
The two pilots needed to beat the existing records - both set in 1981 - by 1%.
For duration that meant staying aloft for about 138 hours and 45 minutes, and for distance they needed to travel about 5,260 miles.
The Two Eagles Balloon team said the landing "occurred at six days, 16 hours and 37 minutes", with the pilots covering the distance of 6,646 miles.
Gas-air balloons are difficult to steer, relying on the differing wind speed and direction at different altitudes.
In order to change height the pilots have only a helium release valve to go down and sandbags to jettison to go up.
The hi-tech "Two Eagles" balloon is made of a strong Kevlar and carbon-fibre composite, but weighs only 220 pounds (100kg).
It is fitted with monitors and other instruments that track their course and compile data to be submitted to record-keepers.
The specially-designed capsule sits beneath a huge helium-filled envelope and is designed to stay aloft for up to 10 days. The pilots live in a closet-like space with a very low ceiling.

RamJam uploaded Southern Rail Tycoon on Thursday , and so far 45,000 people have played the tongue - in - cheek game . The aim is to stop guards from boarding trains , which leads to services being cancelled as profits are collected from passengers . It was inspired by months of cancellations due to an RMT dispute . Once a sufficient number of train guards board on a train and a delayed service eventually departs , the player loses the round, and is presented with a screen showing plummeting profits and irate pixelated commuters storming a virtual London Victoria station. The game, created by Brighton-based indie developer Tom Jackson, under his studio moniker RamJam, has rapidly become a viral sensation. Jackson, a long-time frustrated commuter on the Southern Rail network himself, explained the inspiration behind the satirical hit: 'I spent so many hours delayed on platforms, watching those departure boards mock me, that I just had to channel that frustration into something. It started as a joke among friends, but the more I worked on 'Southern Rail Tycoon', the more I realised how many people could relate to the sheer absurdity of it all.'

The game’s dark humour resonates deeply with those who have endured the real-life chaos on the network. Players must strategically deploy various humorous obstacles, from ‘broken signal’ alerts to ‘leaf on the line’ incidents, all designed to prevent guards from reaching their designated carriages. The more services cancelled, the higher the player's 'tycoon' score, reflecting their fictional mastery over the beleaguered railway. If too many services depart on time, or if guards successfully board multiple trains, the player's 'profit margin' collapses, leading to a swift game over.

Despite its cynical premise, Tom Jackson insists the game is not meant to be a serious political statement, but rather a cathartic outlet. 'It’s about making light of a difficult situation,' he stated. 'It’s satire. It’s a way for people to laugh at the chaos, rather than just fuming about it. We’ve had messages from people in London, Brighton, and all along the line saying how much they appreciate being able to turn their anger into amusement, even if it’s just for a few minutes.' RamJam is now considering updates to Southern Rail Tycoon, including new scenarios and 'disaster' events, as well as a potential mobile version, cementing its status as a cult classic for exasperated commuters everywhere.

Halfpenny's contract at Toulon ends in summer 2016, with Cardiff Blues reported to be interested in re-signing the player.
The 26-year-old left the Blues for France in the summer of 2014.
"He's no different to anyone else. If he is serious about returning we'd be interested to talk to him," said Pivac.
"We don't have an endless budget, but I've said it earlier and nothing has changed.
"If there's any returning Welsh players we'd like to have the opportunity to talk to them just to check what's going on in the market-place and find out their value."
It is likely any return to Wales by the 2013 British and Irish Lions full-back would be on a national dual contract funded 60% by the Welsh Rugby Union.
Under the terms of the agreement between the four regions and the WRU, the player's region of origin would have first refusal on a player returning to Wales - suggesting the Blues would be favourites.
However, flanker Dan Lydiate opted for Ospreys ahead of his old region Newport Gwent Dragons when he returned to Wales from Racing 92.
Another factor could be whether Halfpenny could join a region that qualifies for the 2016-17 European Champions Cup.
Scarlets and Ospreys are Wales' representatives in this season's tournament, and the Blues will have to show a marked improvement in their Pro12 form to qualify for next season.
With Halfpenny having won the tournament with Toulon last season, the chance to play in Europe's premier club event could be a major lure.
After watching his side beat Zebre 20-12 in the Pro12, Pivac also said the Scarlets are keen to hold on to club captain Scott Williams.
The Wales centre - like Halfpenny - is currently out of action after surgery.
Williams is already on a dual contract, which runs out in the summer of 2016.
"I know he's contracted until the end of the season and hopefully we'll get some rugby out of him in that time," said Pivac.
"There's lots of things happening behind the scenes at the moment and I'm not really in a position to give you anything that hasn't already been given out in a press release.
"Scott is our vice captain, one of leaders so we certainly don't want him going anywhere."

Five CCTV cameras have been set up in rural areas across the city . Government figures showed there were 29,253 fly - tipping incidents reported in West Yorkshire during 2023. This alarming figure underscores the persistent problem of illegal waste disposal that blights rural landscapes. The installation of these CCTV cameras is a direct response to this surge, aiming to deter offenders and gather crucial evidence for prosecutions. Steve Hartley, a local environmental enforcement officer, emphasized the importance of these new tools. "Every camera is a step towards holding these irresponsible individuals accountable," he stated. "Fly-tipping costs taxpayers millions annually for cleanup and damages our environment. We are hopeful these covert cameras will significantly reduce incidents and help us identify and prosecute those who blight our areas, sending a clear message that such activities will not be tolerated.

The ex-England Under-18 international, who made his Town debut on the final day of the season, is one of 17 players whose deals are set to expire.
"It's a case of waiting to see what happens," Burton told BBC Shropshire.
"There are a lot of lads out of contract here, because a lot signed two years ago," added 19-year-old Burton.
Speculation has previously linked him with Wolves, Aston Villa and even Glasgow Rangers.
But Newport-born Burton has witnessed the route to the top taken by England's number one, fellow Shropshire lad Joe Hart, who did a full season as Shrewsbury keeper a decade ago.
"I've grown up watching the club," he said. "I want to stay and play for the team as much as I can. We will have to see what happens to everyone.
"It feels like I've been waiting a long time to get on the pitch, because I've been here since I was 10. But I couldn't wish to make my debut for a better team."
The League One club have until 23 May to tell their soon-to-be out-of-contract players if they want to keep them or not.
Shrewsbury, who finished 20th, remained at the third tier of English football by four points in the end, having secured their safety on the penultimate weekend of the season.
Town boss Micky Mellon last week revealed that he is to remain as manager next season, following their relegation near-miss.

Three of those people were involved in a two - car crash in Bangor - on - Dee , Wrexham . Hanjin 's board unanimously agreed to make the court filing at a meeting on Wednesday , a company spokesman said . It faces a cash shortage after failing to persuade key lenders to reschedule debt under a new restructuring plan . Shares of Hanjin remain suspended in Seoul after plunging by as much as 29 % on Tuesday . Hanjin , which is also the world seventh-largest container shipping line, said it has filed for court receivership after its banks withdrew support. The South Korean company's move, following Korea Development Bank's (KDB) decision to halt financial aid, deals a severe blow to global trade, potentially leaving billions of dollars worth of goods stranded. This could become the largest container shipping bankruptcy, disrupting supply chains globally before the peak shopping season. Already, U.S. and Chinese ports refuse Hanjin ships entry, and some vessels have been seized by creditors.

The South Korean government has voiced deep concern, urging domestic rivals like Hyundai Merchant Marine (HMM) to consider taking over some of Hanjin's routes, vessels, and personnel. Financial regulators in Seoul are coordinating efforts to mitigate economic fallout. Hyundai Merchant Marine (HMM), itself recently restructured, has expressed readiness to cooperate with government plans to stabilize the market. This might involve acquiring Hanjin’s healthy assets, such as port terminals or select ships, to ensure service continuity. Details are pending court proceedings in Seoul.

Creditors, led by KDB, found Hanjin's self-rescue proposals insufficient by the September 4 deadline, leading to negotiation collapse. This signals Hanjin Shipping's likely end, prompting significant reshuffling in global shipping alliances as other major carriers absorb its market share. The incident highlights severe challenges facing the broader shipping sector, long struggling with overcapacity and weak demand. Focus is now on the Seoul court's actions and swift asset transfer to operators like Hyundai Merchant Marine (HMM) to limit widespread disruption.

The Very Reverend Martin Thrower , 56 , rector of Hadleigh , Suffolk , held his mobile phone over the top of a toilet cubicle , Norwich Crown Court heard . Thrower was arrested at a shopping centre in Ipswich in August 2016 . He admitted two counts of voyeurism at a previous hearing and his sentence was suspended for 24 months . Thrower was ordered to complete a 60 - day rehabilitation activity requirement, aimed at addressing his offending behaviour and preventing re-offending. As part of his sentence, he was also made the subject of a Sexual Harm Prevention Order (SHPO) for five years. This order imposes strict conditions, including restrictions on his use of internet-enabled devices and a prohibition on entering any public lavatories. Furthermore, Thrower was ordered to pay £2,500 in prosecution costs and a victim surcharge. The court heard details of how the Very Reverend Martin Thrower, who had served as the rector of Hadleigh in Suffolk for 15 years, had committed these offences. His reprehensible actions came to light when he was observed acting suspiciously at a shopping centre in Ipswich, specifically in the men's public toilets, leading to his arrest in August 2016. During the sentencing hearing at Norwich Crown Court, the presiding judge highlighted the profound breach of trust involved in Thrower's conduct, given his prominent and respected role within the Church of England and the local Hadleigh community. While acknowledging Thrower's early admission of guilt and expressions of remorse, the judge unequivocally underscored the seriousness of the voyeurism offences and the distress caused to his victims. The court took into account his previous good character and long service to the church as mitigating factors, which were instrumental in the decision to suspend his prison sentence for 24 months, but firmly emphasized the necessity for both punitive measures and active rehabilitation. This high-profile case sent ripples through the Hadleigh community and the wider diocese of St Edmundsbury and Ipswich, raising questions about accountability and the profound impact of such a conviction on a figure once held in high esteem.

Macauley Bonne gave the U 's a 69th - minute lead , but the Spireites , who played more than 70 minutes with 10 men , soon equalised with a penalty . " Teams are vulnerable after they 've scored . Our game management has got to be a lot better , " said Keen , whose side whose side, Colchester United, ultimately succumbed to a frustrating 2-1 defeat against Chesterfield. "It's infuriating to concede almost immediately after you've taken the lead, especially when you have a man advantage for such a significant period of the game," Keen lamented, his frustration palpable. "Macauley Bonne took his goal so well, a really good finish, and that should have been the turning point for us to go on and secure all three points. Instead, we mentally switched off, allowed them back into the game far too easily, and then failed to respond adequately to their eventual winner. The penalty decision itself was debatable, yes, but our reaction to it and the subsequent equaliser was simply non-existent. We talk about showing character and resilience, but today we displayed very little of it when it truly mattered most. We need to be far more professional, more focused, and much more streetwise. The players have to grasp the fact that every single minute of every game counts, especially when you are fighting for every point in a demanding division like this. We allowed ourselves to be severely punished for a clear lack of concentration and game management. This isn't the first time we've let a strong position slip, and it's a worrying pattern that we absolutely, unequivocally must break. It's simply not good enough. We effectively gifted them a point, and ultimately, three. We've got to be more ruthless in seeing games out, both in our attacking play and, crucially, in our defensive discipline. We're creating enough chances, which is a positive, but we're conceding soft goals at the other end. That combination is a recipe for disaster. We need to be tougher, both physically and mentally, to grind out results. This outcome feels like a massive, massive missed opportunity, one that could potentially cost the U's dearly as the season progresses. We simply cannot afford these lapses in concentration if we are to climb the league table and achieve our objectives.

Colin Capp , 23 , of Scotland , attacked Darren Thomas , 45 , while he slept in their cell on Wing B. Consultant forensic psychiatrist Dr Melanie Croy told the jury Mr Capp 's ability to form rational judgement was impaired because of his mental illness . Mr Capp admits killing Mr Thomas but denies murder . Appearing for the prosecution, Mr. John Smith QC, told the jury that while Mr Capp's mental health issues were acknowledged, they did not amount to a defence of diminished responsibility or negate the intent to kill. He argued that the brutal nature of the attack on Mr Thomas, carried out while he was vulnerable and asleep in their shared cell on Wing B, demonstrated a clear intention. Mr Smith highlighted the evidence of pre-meditation, suggesting Mr Capp had planned the assault. Dr Croy, cross-examined by the prosecution, reiterated her assessment that Mr Capp suffered from paranoid schizophrenia, leading to a severely distorted perception of reality. She elaborated on his delusional beliefs, which had intensified in the confined environment of Wing B, particularly in relation to his cellmate, Mr Thomas. She stated that while he understood the physical act of killing, his capacity for moral judgment and rational decision-making was profoundly compromised. Prison officers also described Mr Capp's erratic behaviour in the days leading up to the attack. The defence, led by Ms Sarah Jones, countered that Mr Capp's actions were a direct consequence of his severe mental illness, which had been inadequately managed within the prison system. Ms Jones emphasised Dr Croy's expert opinion, arguing Mr Capp suffered from an abnormality of mental functioning which substantially impaired his ability to understand his conduct, form rational judgment, or exercise self-control. She painted a picture of a young man from Scotland whose untreated condition spiralled out of control, leading to the tragic death of Darren Thomas. The trial continues, with further medical evidence expected before deliberations begin on the complex interplay between mental health and criminal culpability.

It comes after Darren ' Birdie ' Bird 's image - showing the mascot " paying his respects " to Sir Terry , who died on Sunday - was shared thousands of times on social media . Pudsey has a tear running down his face and is holding a microphone, a poignant symbol of Sir Terry Wogan's iconic voice and his unparalleled dedication to the Children in Need appeal. The digital artwork, a creation of Darren 'Birdie' Bird, swiftly became a powerful visual representation of the nation's collective grief following the news of Sir Terry's death on Sunday. For generations, Sir Terry had been the reassuring, witty, and warm voice of Children in Need, guiding the annual telethon with his inimitable charm. This particular image of Pudsey, the beloved charity mascot, weeping and clutching a mic, perfectly captured the profound sense of loss felt by millions who considered Wogan a national treasure. The simplicity and emotional resonance of Bird's design saw it shared relentlessly across platforms, becoming a central point for heartfelt tributes and shared memories of the broadcaster's profound impact on public life and his tireless work for charity. It serves as a testament to Sir Terry's enduring legacy and the deep affection he inspired in countless hearts across the country.
