However , he sustained a calf injury as the Italians fought back to win 2 - 1 . " We will have to see how Vincent is on Wednesday , " said City manager Manuel Pellegrini . " We will check and see how serious the injury is . " Kompany , 29 , was replaced by Nicolas Otamendi - City 's £32 million summer signing from Valencia. The Belgium international had been in outstanding form at the start of the season, scoring two goals in four Premier League games and leading a defence that had not conceded a single goal prior to Tuesday’s Champions League opener. His forced withdrawal against Juventus is a significant blow for Manuel Pellegrini’s side, especially given Kompany’s history of calf problems. The City captain has been plagued by similar injuries throughout his career, leading to concerns about his long-term availability.

Pellegrini expressed his immediate worry in the post-match media briefing, acknowledging the severity of losing such a pivotal player. "It's a very important injury for Vincent," he reiterated. "He was playing very well and we hope it's not a serious one. We will know more after he has a scan." The manager also confirmed that Sergio Aguero, who had been substituted in the first half of Saturday's Premier League win over Crystal Palace, was not fit enough to feature against the Italians. The absence of both Kompany and Aguero highlights the squad depth challenges that City might face as they navigate a demanding schedule of domestic and European fixtures. The team’s strong start to the Premier League season has built high expectations, and maintaining that momentum will require all players to stay fit and perform.

The defensive partnership between Kompany and Otamendi was one that City fans were eager to see develop, with the Argentine having been eased into the squad. Now, Otamendi is likely to be thrust into a starting role much sooner than anticipated, potentially alongside Eliaquim Mangala or Martin Demichelis. The loss to Juventus, despite Kompany's early influence in pressuring Giorgio Chiellini for the own goal, marked a disappointing start to City’s Champions League campaign. The focus will now shift to how Pellegrini reshapes his defence and inspires a response from his team in the upcoming derby against Manchester United. The media will undoubtedly scrutinize City’s defensive performance in the absence of their influential captain, Vincent Kompany, as they aim to bounce back from this early European setback and continue their impressive domestic form.

West Yorkshire Police confirmed last month that 16,000 tickets issued by police community support officers ( PCSO ) were not valid due because of an " administrative error " . But , the force said there was " no basis in law " for refunds , which would have " come from the public purse " . Many of the drivers paid the fines, unaware of the underlying error. The revelation sparked considerable public outcry and anger among those affected, who felt unfairly penalised by the West Yorkshire Police. Drivers expressed frustration that the force was acknowledging the invalidity of the tickets while simultaneously refusing any form of recompense. Legal experts weighed in, questioning the ethical implications of retaining funds collected unlawfully, even if there was no direct legal precedent for a refund. Some argued that while the law might not explicitly mandate refunds in such a unique administrative error scenario, the principle of unjust enrichment should apply, where one party should not benefit from another's loss caused by their own mistake.

The situation put the West Yorkshire Police under significant pressure to explain why such a fundamental error occurred and why transparency about the issue took so long. Critics pointed out that the public's trust in the police, particularly in the impartiality and correctness of their enforcement actions, could be severely damaged. The Police and Crime Commissioner for West Yorkshire acknowledged the serious nature of the administrative error and stated that a full internal review was underway to understand how the invalid tickets were issued by PCSOs for such an extended period without detection. This review aimed to identify weaknesses in the internal processes and implement robust measures to prevent a recurrence.

For the many individuals who had already paid their tickets, often under the threat of further penalties or points on their license, the news was a bitter pill. Some indicated they would explore avenues for collective legal action, seeking advice on whether a class-action lawsuit could compel the force to refund the monies. Consumer rights groups also got involved, advocating on behalf of the affected drivers and calling for a clearer legal framework to address situations where administrative errors by public bodies lead to financial detriment for citizens. The incident highlighted a significant loophole in the system, where a clear administrative blunder by the West Yorkshire Police left thousands of citizens out of pocket with seemingly no recourse, raising fundamental questions about accountability and citizen protection when dealing with official enforcement. The cost of individual legal challenges for the drivers would likely outweigh the value of the tickets, further complicating their options. The PCSO role and the scope of their powers were also re-examined in light of the incident.

Ahmed Mohamed 's father , Mohamed El - Hassan Mohamed , said he had pulled all his children from schools in the area . According to Mr Mohamed the arrest of the 14 - year - old had a harmful effect . Ahmed 's arrest has been sharply criticised and the charges against him were quickly dropped . Ahmed was arrested at MacArthur High School in Irving, Texas, after bringing a homemade clock to school that teachers and officials mistook for a bomb. The incident rapidly escalated, drawing national and international attention and igniting a widespread debate about Islamophobia and racial profiling. Ahmed, an aspiring inventor, had merely intended to show off his creation to his engineering teacher. Instead, the clock’s circuit board and wires, visible inside a pencil case, led to his apprehension, interrogation without parental presence, fingerprinting, and a trip to a juvenile detention center.

The public outcry was immediate and immense. Prominent figures, including President Barack Obama and Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg, offered their support, inviting Ahmed to the White House and Facebook headquarters, respectively. The hashtag #IStandWithAhmed trended globally, highlighting concerns about overreactions and bias in school disciplinary actions.

For Mohamed El-Hassan Mohamed, Ahmed's father, the experience was deeply disturbing. He openly stated his belief that the school's actions were driven by discrimination and Islamophobia, prompting his decision to remove all his children from the local school system. The family later moved to Qatar after Ahmed received a scholarship, though they eventually returned to the United States. The incident became a defining moment in discussions about systemic biases within educational and law enforcement institutions.

Four men deny attempting to smuggle 35 people into Tilbury Docks , Essex . One man died in the container . Basildon Crown Court heard one defendant been caught in France with migrants in the back of his lorry 11 days before the Tilbury incident . Timothy Murphy from Londonderry was fined √Ç¬£5,000 in August . Prosecutor Michael Goodwin told the court that the 35 migrants, including 15 children, were discovered on August 16 last year inside a container on the MV Titania, which had arrived at Tilbury Docks from Zeebrugge, Belgium. Conditions within the sealed container were described as “inhumane and life-threatening,” with temperatures soaring and oxygen levels depleting rapidly during the 10-hour voyage. The court heard that the victims had been deliberately locked inside the unit.

Mr. Goodwin explained that port officials heard unusual noises coming from within the container. Upon opening it, they found terrified and struggling individuals, many suffering from severe dehydration and hyperthermia. Among them was Meet Singh, 47, from Afghanistan, who tragically died during the journey. A post-mortem examination concluded that his death was caused by a combination of dehydration and hyperthermia.

The prosecution alleges that the four defendants, Stephen McLaughlin, 31; Martin McGlinchey, 49; Christopher Murphy, 20; and Timothy Murphy, 33, all from Londonderry, were part of an organised criminal conspiracy to smuggle people into the UK for financial gain. Mr. Goodwin highlighted Timothy Murphy's previous conviction in France, where he was caught attempting to transport 15 migrants in his lorry. This incident, just days before the Tilbury tragedy, suggested a sophisticated and repeated enterprise.

The court heard evidence that the defendants had been in regular contact via burner phones, coordinating their movements leading up to the incident. CCTV footage and phone data linked them to the vehicle carrying the container and to locations near Zeebrugge. The prosecution argued that the defendants were fully aware of the dangerous conditions the migrants would endure and showed a callous disregard for human life.

All four defendants deny a charge of conspiracy to facilitate illegal entry into the UK and a charge of manslaughter in relation to Mr. Singh’s death. The trial at Basildon Crown Court is expected to last several weeks, with further evidence to be presented regarding the planning and execution of the smuggling operation and the role each defendant played. The focus remains on establishing the extent of their knowledge and involvement in this tragic event, which ultimately cost a man his life and put dozens of others in extreme peril at Tilbury Docks in Essex.

Chief Inspector of Prisons Peter Clarke published his findings following unannounced inspections . Challenges included staff shortages and increased use of new psychoactive substances , leading to more " unpredictable and violent behaviour " . But inspectors also found good staff - prisoner relationships and a " good range " of training and education . Despite safety declining since 2013 , Mr Clarke described it as a " mixed picture of progress throughout the prison estate. While some institutions demonstrated resilience and effective leadership, Peter Clarke's report highlighted a persistent struggle with systemic issues that continued to undermine the safe and effective operation of many establishments across England and Wales. The surge in violence, often linked directly to the ready availability of illicit drugs like spice, placed immense strain on both resources and the morale of dedicated staff.

A significant challenge identified by Clarke was the ongoing problem of staff retention. This issue, exacerbated by the demanding and often dangerous work environment, meant that many prisons struggled to deliver a full daily regime, leading to extended periods of lock-up for prisoners. Such reduced out-of-cell time often fueled frustration and further escalated tensions within already volatile environments. Crucially, the report by Clarke also drew attention to the critical issue of prison capacity. Many establishments were operating significantly above their certified normal accommodation. This widespread overcrowding, where cells designed for a single inmate were frequently housing two or even three, directly contributed to the documented decline in safety and the notable increase in violent incidents. It severely limited personal space, heightened friction between inmates, and made effective supervision considerably more difficult for staff.

Peter Clarke underscored the urgent need for sustained investment, not just in the physical infrastructure of prisons, but vitally in the recruitment, retention, and well-being of frontline staff. He emphasized that prioritizing the mental and physical health of both prisoners and staff was essential for creating environments truly conducive to rehabilitation, rather than merely containment. The Chief Inspector warned that without tackling these deep-seated structural issues, including the fundamental mismatch between the rising prison population and the available certified normal accommodation, the risk of further deterioration in safety and order within the nation's prisons remained unacceptably high. His findings provided a sobering assessment, urging the government to adopt a comprehensive and strategic approach to adequately resource and manage the future integrity of the entire prison system.

Games will also be held in Bangladesh before the competition returns to India once polling has concluded . The world 's biggest elections start on 12 May and security forces can not be spared from their crucial duties during this period. This forced the initial phase of the Indian Premier League (IPL) to be moved out of the country. The first leg of the tournament, featuring many of the world's top cricketers, was successfully staged in the United Arab Emirates (UAE). This innovative approach ensured that the popular Twenty20 cricket league could continue without disruption, maintaining its high standards of play and global viewership. The decision to split the tournament across multiple international venues – first the UAE, then Bangladesh, and finally back to India – highlights the logistical complexities and flexibility required to manage such a massive sporting event amidst national priorities. The cricket board has prioritised the safety of players and fans, making necessary adjustments to the IPL schedule. While South Africa has hosted parts of the IPL in the past, the current arrangements in the UAE and Bangladesh were deemed most suitable given the timing and logistical considerations. Fans eagerly await the return of the IPL to its home grounds, where the final stages and play-offs are expected to generate immense excitement.

The life - size bronze effigy of the Native American stands in Gravesend , Kent , where she died on her journey home to Virginia in 1617 . Historic England has renewed its Grade II listed status and updated details of her life and role in Transatlantic history , confirming the monument's significance in commemorating Pocahontas, known also as Matoaka. The statue, erected in 1958, serves as a poignant reminder of her brief but impactful time in England, where she was presented to King James I and Queen Anne. Her story embodies the early, complex interactions between European settlers and Native American communities, particularly her marriage to English tobacco planter John Rolfe, which was instrumental in a period of peace for the early Jamestown colony.

The updated Historic England listing now explicitly acknowledges her Algonquian heritage and the often-misrepresented narratives surrounding her life, highlighting the agency she exercised within challenging circumstances. This recognition underscores the effigy's importance not merely as a local landmark in Gravesend, Kent, but as a national symbol of a pivotal moment in global history. The Grade II listing ensures the continued preservation of this unique memorial, reflecting its special architectural and historical interest. It emphasizes her tragic death at a young age in Gravesend before she could return to her native Virginia, underscoring the profound human cost of early colonial expansion and intercultural exchange. The statue, therefore, invites contemplation on themes of cultural encounter, diplomacy, and the lasting legacy of those who bridged vastly different worlds.

They lost by seven wickets after being bowled out for just 90 in a rain - shortened match at the Riverside . " We fell a long way short . The game was reduced , but still to be bowled out for 90 in 22 overs is not good enough , " Durham head coach Jon Lewis told BBC Newcastle. "When you're chasing such a low total, you expect your top order to step up and build a foundation, but we just never got going. It was a really poor performance from start to finish, especially considering the conditions were easing. We knew Worcestershire would come hard at us, and they did, but we simply crumbled under the pressure. It's frustrating because we've shown glimpses of what we can do in other games at the Riverside, but this was a significant step backwards." Durham captain Scott Borthwick added, "It's certainly not what we wanted. We prepared well, but the execution wasn't there. Losing early wickets put us on the back foot, and we couldn't recover. Credit to Worcestershire, they bowled exceptionally well and put us under constant pressure. We need to learn from this quickly and ensure we bounce back strongly in our next fixture. We have a lot of talented players in this squad, and we know we're capable of much better. We'll be working hard to address the issues that arose today and come back stronger." Fast bowler Chris Rushworth, a key figure for Durham, echoed the sentiment of disappointment. "It's tough to take," Rushworth commented. "We pride ourselves on our fight, and today we just didn't show enough of it. Dropping catches and misfields at crucial moments didn't help our cause either. We gave away too many easy runs and then failed to make enough ourselves. It's a collective failure, and we all need to look in the mirror." The defeat leaves Durham with much to reflect on as they look to improve their white-ball form.

31 March 2015 Last updated at 18:32 BST It 's presented by Millie from Newsround. Today, Millie Innes, star of the hit CBBC show Millie Inbetween, joins us to bring you all the latest news and sport, plus an exclusive look at how Meghan Trainor is dominating the music charts and why her message resonates with so many young fans.

Fewer animals were counted on Scotland's east coast and in Orkney in surveys by St Andrews University Sea Mammal Research Unit.
But the work commissioned by Scottish Natural Heritage (SNH), found an increase in harbour seals on the west coast.
Between Cape Wrath and Ullapool, 1,095 animals were recorded.
In 2008, a survey counted 2,687.
Sightings of harbour seals, also known as common seals, have been declining for several years, with the latest research suggesting the trend is continuing.
Between Aberlady Bay in East Lothian, 213 were spotted compared with 459 seven years ago.
The unit did not have enough time to survey the coast from Aberlady Bay down to the Scottish Borders.
At the Firth of Tay and Eden Estuary Special Area of Conservation, 50 seals were counted - the lowest figure so far recorded in that area. Previously, 78 were seen.
In Orkney, the latest research recorded 1,865 compared with 2,687 in 2010.

This Is For My Girls was written by Diane Warren - whose previous credits include I Don't Want To Miss A Thing and Un-Break My Heart.
She described the song - a strident, girl power anthem - as "We Are the World meets Lady Marmalade".
Obama released the single ahead of her keynote speech at the SXSW festival.
She will talk about her Let Girls Learn initiative, which is aimed at boosting education rates amongst adolescent girls around the world.
Several of the performers on the track, including Missy Elliott and Diane Warren, will then join her on a panel about the initiative, as well as Sophia Bush and Queen Latifah, who will moderate the discussion.
This Is For My Girls combines jazzy horn stabs with a propulsive drum beat, giving the song a militaristic feel.
The lyrics mostly comprise generic statements of empowerment - "Don't take nothing from nobody"; "It's all about respect"; "Stand strong forever" - which have been a standard component of female-fronted R&B since the turn of the millennium.
Other vocalists featured on the track include Janelle Monae, Glee actress Lea Michele, Disney star Zendaya, 16-year-old Motown artist Jadagrace, and Beyonce proteges Chloe & Halle.
All of the artists waived their fees, meaning proceeds will go directly to the Let Girls Learn campaign.
"We haven't had an anthem like this in a while," Warren told Billboard.
"I envisioned the record being with all these different women, never just one girl singing on it.
"With Kelly Rowland on it, it's almost like an updated Destiny's Child record. I think it can be a huge worldwide anthem. I hope it becomes that."
The single is available exclusively on iTunes, while Obama's speech at the SXSW festival will be streamed live on makers.com from 16:00 GMT.

World heavyweight champion Fury , 27 , who expressed views on women , abortion and homosexuality , has been asked to attend a meeting in the new year . The BBBofC met to discuss the matter on Wednesday before informing Fury that he must meet with the board . The Briton has denied he is a homophobe and claimed he is " uniting the world " This upcoming meeting with the British Boxing Board of Control is expected to be a crucial one, as the organization seeks to address the widespread condemnation sparked by the boxer’s controversial remarks. Public outcry intensified following comments where Fury equated homosexuality and abortion with the end of the world, and made disparaging remarks about women.

The firestorm led to significant pressure. Over 140,000 people signed an online petition calling for the Briton to be removed from the BBC Sports Personality of the Year shortlist. Despite the controversy, the BBC maintained Fury would remain on the list, citing that the decision was based on sporting achievement. This stance further fueled debate about the responsibility of public figures.

Furthermore, his comments prompted an investigation by Greater Manchester Police (GMP). The police force confirmed they had received complaints regarding his comments, which were being assessed for potential hate crime implications. While the GMP later clarified no specific crime had been recorded, the police inquiry underscored the seriousness with which his remarks were viewed.

Fury, who secured his world titles after defeating Wladimir Klitschko, has consistently maintained that his comments were taken out of context and that he is not a prejudiced individual, insisting he respects all people. Despite his defence, the ongoing controversy has cast a significant shadow over his boxing achievements and raised uncomfortable questions for the sport. The BBBofC meeting is anticipated to clarify whether Fury will face any disciplinary action, ranging from a reprimand to a fine or even a suspension, depending on the Board's assessment of his conduct and compliance with their code of ethics.

McAuley , 50 , with an address at Cavan Bank Walk , Ballyconnell , County Cavan , also pleaded guilty to producing a knife during an altercation that occurred in Kilderry, Kilnaleck, on October 20 last year. The court heard that the incident involved a dispute over land near his residence, escalated when McAuley brandished the weapon. Gardaí responded to reports of a disturbance and apprehended him at the scene. His solicitor explained that his client was under significant stress at the time. The judge emphasized the gravity of using a knife in a public place, noting the potential for serious injury, and remanded McAuley on continuing bail until sentencing, which was adjourned for a probation report. This report will consider the impact on the community in Cavan.

Ashley Broomhall trekked to the summit of 3,560 ft ( 1,085 m ) Snowdon in Snowdonia before tackling Ben Nevis . It took him seven hours to walk up and down the 4,406 ft ( 1,344 m ) Scottish peak near Fort William . On the way up he had a snowball fight with other walkers . He now plans to walk 3,208 ft ( 978 m ) Scafell Pike in the Lake District . Mr Broomhall , from Whitchurch in Shropshire , has been doing the walks to raise money for Cancer Research UK . He was inspired to take on the gruelling challenge after seeing the devastating impact of cancer on close friends and family members. He believes that every step he takes, and every pound he raises, contributes to vital research that could save lives in the future.

His ascent of Snowdon, the highest peak in Wales, provided a challenging start to his mountaineering endeavours, offering stunning views of Snowdonia National Park despite periods of cloud and wind. The subsequent climb of Ben Nevis, the UK's highest mountain, proved to be an even more demanding test of his physical and mental fortitude. He recounted battling the notoriously unpredictable Scottish weather conditions, which ranged from clear spells to biting winds and snow flurries, even in what is considered late spring. The impromptu snowball fight on Ben Nevis's upper slopes offered a brief, memorable moment of camaraderie and fun amidst the arduous trek, highlighting the shared spirit among those conquering the formidable peak near Fort William. The descent, often as challenging as the ascent, required intense concentration and resilience, but the thought of the critical cause kept him focused.

With two of the UK's three highest peaks now conquered, Mr Broomhall is eagerly anticipating his final challenge: Scafell Pike in the Lake District. Completing Scafell Pike will mark the culmination of his personal 'Three Peaks Challenge', an iconic feat that involves climbing the highest mountains in Scotland, England, and Wales within a set period. He understands that while Scafell Pike is the lowest of the three, it presents its own unique difficulties, including rugged terrain and potentially tricky navigation, especially if weather conditions are poor.

Ashley Broomhall has set a fundraising target of £1,500 for Cancer Research UK and has already made significant progress towards that goal, having raised over £900 through a combination of online donations and sponsorship from friends, family, and local businesses. He expressed immense gratitude for the generosity shown by his supporters so far. "The support I've received has been overwhelming," said Mr Broomhall. "Knowing that people are backing me and contributing to such an important cause really motivates me to keep going, even when the climbs get tough. Every single donation helps fund groundbreaking research into new treatments and ultimately, a cure." He hopes that by sharing his journey, he can encourage more people to donate or consider their own fundraising challenges. Donations to Ashley Broomhall's efforts can be made via his dedicated JustGiving page, which can be found by searching for his name or his specific challenge details online. He remains committed to his fundraising mission, aiming to help contribute to a future where cancer no longer devastates lives.

The Citroen driver from Dungannon won three out of the four stages in the Tour de Course.
Ogier stayed within touching distance of the Meeke, who is aiming to follow up his dramatic victory in Rally Mexico with another win.
Huyundai's Thierry Neuville holds third, 25.8 seconds off the lead.
Meeke took control early on the first Asphalt round of the season, winning the opening stage before adding two more stage wins before the end of the day .
Four-time world champion Ogier was fastest in SS3 in his M-Sport Ford to cut Meeke's advantage to just over eight seconds, however he responded on the final stage to extend his advantage over 10 seconds.
"It's been a good day," said Meeke, 37. "You always have to be wary of Seb, because he never gives up. But I'm comfortable with my pace, so let's see how we go on Saturday."
Meeke's Citroen team-mate Craig Breen holds an impressive fourth, with the Waterford driver locked in a tight battle with Spaniard Dani Sordo.

The firm plans to introduce a new fleet of 52 driver - only - operated ( DOO ) trains from 2020 . None of the permanent guards or guard managers would be forced to quit their employment , the company said . RMT union said it was in formal dispute with Merseyrail and its 220 members would be balloted for industrial action, including strikes, over the plans. The union claims removing guards compromises passenger safety and attacks a vital role.

RMT General Secretary Mick Cash said: 'Merseyrail’s announcement is a kick in the teeth for staff and public. Removing guards undermines safety and accessibility. We won't let Merseyrail put profits over people. Our members are resolute; we'll vigorously campaign to protect the guard's role and ensure safe services. This fight is about safety and security, especially in emergencies. Merseyrail left us no choice but to ballot.'

Merseyrail Managing Director John Tilley responded by stressing safety, stating new DOO trains use advanced technology like driver-monitored CCTV. He said: 'Safety is our priority. All permanent guards and guard managers will be redeployed into new customer service roles on platforms, with no pay loss or compulsory redundancies. This enhances customer service and aligns with modern UK rail practices. We urge RMT to engage constructively, avoiding disruptive industrial action that harms passengers and the local economy.'

The dispute reflects the national controversy over DOO operations, which caused strikes elsewhere. Merseyrail's decision to proceed with its 2020 rollout despite union opposition indicates potential significant disruption across Merseyside.

Scotland 's Anderson averaged 107.68 - the highest in the tournament so far - compared to his Dutch opponent 's 102.3 . The pair also threw 20 180s in total at London 's Alexandra Palace Scotland 's Anderson averaged 107.68 - the highest in the tournament so far - compared to his Dutch opponent Raymond van Barneveld's 102.3. The pair also threw 20 180s in total at London 's Alexandra Palace, in what was hailed as one of the greatest matches in World Darts Championship history. The thrilling quarter-final encounter saw both players produce exceptional performances, showcasing their legendary skill and determination on the biggest stage. Anderson, a two-time world champion, demonstrated why he is considered one of the sport's all-time greats, maintaining incredible consistency and accuracy under immense pressure. Van Barneveld, himself a five-time world champion, pushed 'The Flying Scotsman' all the way, delighting the packed crowd with his vintage form and dramatic scoring bursts. The electric atmosphere at 'Ally Pally' amplified every dart, with fans roaring their approval for the high-quality play from start to finish. This monumental clash, which ultimately saw Anderson emerge victorious after a hard-fought battle, firmly cemented its place in the annals of darts, setting a new benchmark for individual and combined scoring in the prestigious event. Anderson's dominant display positions him as a strong favourite moving into the semi-finals, while Van Barneveld's valiant effort reminded everyone of his enduring class and ability to compete at the very pinnacle of the sport.

It was announced on Wednesday that the East Midlands Congenital Heart Centre , at Glenfield Hospital , was to stop children 's surgery services . It was one of 10 units under review nationally with the intention to focus expertise in fewer locations . The charity Heartlink said it would not accept the judgement . A spokesman for the charity , John Rigby , said : " We 're going to take stock , listen to what our reps have said, and then we will plan our next steps. This is absolutely not the end of the fight for the East Midlands Congenital Heart Centre. We believe this decision is flawed and will ultimately harm children and families across the UK. Heartlink will explore every avenue, including legal challenges and further campaigning, to reverse this damaging judgement."

This decision, part of NHS England's 'Safe and Sustainable' review, aims to consolidate specialist services into fewer, larger centres to improve outcomes for children with complex congenital heart conditions. While proponents cite better surgical results and comprehensive care through concentrated expertise, opponents like Heartlink argue that closing established units, especially those with strong reputations, fragments care and increases travel burden for families in regions like the East Midlands.

Glenfield Hospital's children's heart unit is also uniquely known for its Extracorporeal Membrane Oxygenation (ECMO) service, a vital life support system for failing hearts and lungs. It is one of only four paediatric ECMO centres in the UK. Though the ECMO service wasn't explicitly part of the surgical closure, clinicians and parents worry about the long-term viability of a specialist ECMO unit without a co-located surgical team. This interdependency is a core argument for campaigners like John Rigby, who fear that dismantling the surgical component will inevitably weaken or lead to the loss of the ECMO service, a crucial national resource. The future of specialist paediatric care in the UK is now under intense scrutiny, with questions raised about whether centralisation truly benefits all.

Hina Rabbani Khar 's remarks came hours after the two armies agreed to " de - escalate " tensions after a meeting of their chiefs of operations . Tensions have risen following deadly exchanges along the border last week . The violence has plunged the neighbours into the worst crisis in relations since the Mumbai attacks of 2008 , blamed on militants based in Pakistan . " Instead of issuing belligerent statements by the military and political leaders, it is imperative that both sides show restraint and engage in meaningful dialogue to de-escalate tensions along the Line of Control. The recent violence, following the deadly exchanges last week, has indeed brought the two nuclear-armed neighbours to the precipice of a dangerous confrontation, reminiscent of the heightened animosity seen in the aftermath of the Mumbai attacks of 2008, which India squarely blames on Pakistan-based militants.

Hina Rabbani Khar's remarks, therefore, carry significant weight at this critical juncture. As a former top diplomat, her call for calm and adherence to the agreed-upon de-escalation mechanisms underscores the diplomatic path forward. Ms Khar's emphasis on finding a peaceful resolution, rather than resorting to aggressive rhetoric or military posturing, highlights the need for a sustained effort to build trust and prevent further bloodshed on the border. The focus should now be on ensuring that the understanding reached by the chiefs of operations is implemented in spirit and letter, thereby paving the way for a more stable environment. Both nations must prioritize the well-being of their citizens over jingoistic narratives, working towards a future where such crises do not repeatedly threaten regional peace. The international community, too, has a role to play in encouraging both India and Pakistan to maintain channels of communication and address their core disputes through peaceful means, rather than allowing cross-border incidents to spiral out of control.

Cormack , a former chief executive of Aberdeen , sold his software company for ¬£630 m last year . " I can offer both financial support and my time to the club , " Cormack told the Aberdeen website . " I look forward to attracting American investment and strategic partnerships [ to ] help AFC maximise its potential . " Cormack will work with existing board members , including chairman Stewart Milne , while splitting his time between Atlanta and the north east of Scotland . Cormack's move signifies a new era of ambition for the Pittodrie club, long reliant on its loyal local fanbase and shrewd financial management. His vast experience in building and scaling successful tech companies, particularly his ability to identify and leverage growth opportunities, is seen as a major asset that could transform Aberdeen's commercial and global reach. The club has openly sought international investment for some time, with chairman Stewart Milne expressing a consistent desire to expand its network beyond traditional Scottish boundaries. Cormack's American base in Atlanta provides a crucial bridge to the lucrative US market, offering significant potential for new sponsorships, merchandising, and even strategic club partnerships that could benefit both on-field performance and commercial revenues. His stated focus on 'maximising potential' is widely understood to encompass not just player development and consistent on-field success, but also the acceleration of the club's crucial infrastructure projects, including the new state-of-the-art training facilities and the proposed stadium at Kingsford. The synergy between Cormack's modern business acumen and Stewart Milne's deep understanding of Scottish football and local dynamics promises a formidable leadership duo for Aberdeen. Fans across Scotland, and particularly in the north-east, are highly optimistic that this injection of expertise and capital will propel Aberdeen back to consistent European qualification and allow them to more regularly challenge the traditional dominance of the Glasgow giants. The board believes that Cormack’s global network and entrepreneurial spirit will be instrumental in securing the club's long-term financial future, moving it towards a more self-sustaining model that combines high sporting ambition with robust financial prudence. His commitment to dedicating significant personal time, alongside his financial support, underscores the seriousness of his intent to help his boyhood club flourish on a truly broader, international stage.

Investigators think the blast was caused by a female suicide bomber from the Islamic State group . Correspondents say Turkey is cracking down on the militants , after previously being accused of ignoring them . But the blast triggered violent protest in Istanbul , with police using water cannon , teargas and rubber bullets . Friday 's bomb hit a group of youth activists planning to cross into Syria to help rebuild the town of Kobane . A video shows the group holding a news conference to discuss their plans , when an explosion rips through the crowd. The chaotic footage, widely circulated online, shows bodies strewn across the ground, thick smoke billowing upwards, and survivors screaming amidst the debris. At least 32 people were killed in the attack in Suruc, a town bordering Syria, and over 100 were wounded. The vast majority of the victims were members of the Federation of Socialist Youth Associations (SGDF), who had gathered at the Amara Culture Centre before their planned journey to Kobane. Their mission was to help reconstruct the Syrian Kurdish town, which had been devastated by a four-month siege by Islamic State militants last year before being liberated by Kurdish forces.

The Turkish authorities swiftly identified the perpetrator as a female suicide bomber with suspected links to the Islamic State group, also known as ISIS or Daesh. This attack marked a significant escalation of the conflict onto Turkish soil, putting immense pressure on President Recep Tayyip Erdogan’s government. Critics had long accused Ankara of turning a blind eye to, or even tacitly supporting, hardline Islamist groups in Syria as part of its strategy to undermine President Bashar al-Assad. However, following the Suruc bombing, Turkey vowed a more aggressive stance. Prime Minister Ahmet Davutoglu condemned the 'barbaric' act and pledged to intensify efforts against all terrorist organizations.

The blast immediately ignited widespread outrage and protests across Turkey, especially in Istanbul, where demonstrators clashed violently with police. The previously mentioned use of water cannon, teargas, and rubber bullets underscores the ferocity of these confrontations, as protesters accused the government of complicity or negligence in failing to prevent such an attack. Many felt the bombing was a direct consequence of Turkey's perceived inaction against Islamic State, particularly along its lengthy border with Syria, which has been a conduit for foreign fighters joining militant groups.

In the days that followed, Turkish security forces launched a series of nationwide raids, detaining hundreds of suspected militants from various groups, including alleged members of the Islamic State. The government stated that these operations were a comprehensive crackdown on terrorism, moving beyond just ISIS to target Kurdish separatist groups like the PKK as well. This broader approach, however, drew criticism from those who believed it was an attempt to deflect attention from the core issue of Islamic State infiltration and to suppress Kurdish political movements. The bombing in Suruc profoundly reshaped Turkey’s domestic security landscape and its foreign policy towards Syria, signalling a more direct and assertive, albeit complex, engagement in the fight against regional extremism.

The Welsh Ambulance Service said it received a 999 call at about 1.45pm BST regarding an incident on Merthyr Road, Merthyr, which required an immediate response. Resources were dispatched to the scene, located close to Prince Charles Hospital, to assess and treat a patient. The service prioritizes urgent calls to ensure the safety and well-being of the community.

An RAF Voyager A330 air - to - air refuelling aircraft will be refitted at a cost of about ¬£10 m. The government says the move will save about ¬£775,000 a year as the plane will be cheaper than chartering flights . The SNP 's Stewart Hosie said there needed to be " absolute transparency " to ensure the " best deal is made on behalf of the tax - payer An RAF Voyager A330 air-to-air refuelling aircraft will be refitted at a cost of about ¬£10m. The government says the move will save about ¬£775,000 a year as the plane will be cheaper than chartering flights. The SNP's Stewart Hosie said there needed to be "absolute transparency" to ensure the "best deal is made on behalf of the tax-payer".

Mr Hosie's demand for "absolute transparency" highlights the need for stringent oversight. He questioned the ¬£10m outlay, despite projected ¬£775,000 annual savings, demanding meticulous scrutiny of long-term value. The refit, involving interior modifications for VIP transport, has drawn criticism. Proponents, however, argue an RAF Voyager A330 offers superior security, flexibility, and availability for ministerial and PM travel over commercial charters.

The government's justification rests on long-term economic benefits and enhanced operational independence. The ¬£10m investment is projected to be recovered via savings in approximately 13 years. Utilizing an existing military asset, rather than chartering private jets, streamlines logistics for sensitive missions. This RAF Voyager A330, primarily a refueller, gains invaluable dual-use capability, maximizing its efficiency within the defence budget.

A Ministry of Defence spokesperson emphasized this project delivers excellent value. The conversion allows the aircraft to maintain core military duties when not needed for VIP transport, preventing the expense of a dedicated executive jet. This multi-role approach is central to an efficient defence estate. Acknowledging the SNP's valid concerns, particularly Stewart Hosie's, the government pledged full disclosure on costs and progress. This aims to dispel "vanity project" perceptions and reaffirm fiscal prudence. Ultimately, the goal is to provide the PM and senior officials with secure, cost-effective travel, seamlessly integrating it with existing military assets. This ensures the RAF Voyager A330 remains a cornerstone for national security and state affairs.

Writing in the Sunday Times , the Plaid Cymru leader urged Wales to " speak with one voice " . The UKIP leader and Welsh first minister will lock horns on the contentious issue of Wales's future within the United Kingdom and its relationship with the European Union post-Brexit. Ms Wood's appeal for unity underscores her party's concern that without a coherent and strong Welsh position, the nation's interests could be marginalized during negotiations with the UK Government and Brussels. She stressed the importance of protecting Welsh jobs, industries, and funding streams, advocating for a bespoke deal that reflects Wales's unique economic and social landscape. The UKIP leader, conversely, is expected to champion a swift and complete departure from the EU, arguing that such a move would unlock significant opportunities for Welsh prosperity and autonomy. This forthcoming debate highlights the deep political divisions across Wales regarding its future path, contrasting sharply with Ms Wood's call for a unified approach to ensure Wales's voice is heard effectively amidst the complexities of a changing UK.

The 19 year - old added 85 for the first wicket with Paul Horton ( 41 ) before Glamorgan claimed three quick wickets , two to teenager Lukas Carey . Dearden then dominated a stand of 90 with Mark Pettini ( 63 not out ) before being bowled by spinner Andrew Salter . Pettini steered the Foxes to a second batting point underneath the lights . Dearden , who was dropped on one , survived a couple of run - out chances in his lengthy vigil of 145 runs, an innings that anchored Leicestershire's first innings and set a challenging total for Glamorgan. His century, a testament to his resilience and growing maturity, included 18 fours and two sixes, played across more than five hours at the crease. It was an innings of two halves, patiently accumulating runs against the new ball before accelerating with Mark Pettini in a partnership that put the visitors on the back foot. The early scares, being dropped and almost run out, only seemed to steel his resolve, as he focused on building a substantial total for his team. His dismissal by Andrew Salter, a rare lapse in concentration, came from a ball that spun sharply back into him, ending a truly memorable individual performance.

With Dearden gone, Leicestershire still needed to consolidate. Mark Pettini, who had played an excellent supporting role, then took on the mantle of primary aggressor. He found an able partner in Ned Eckersley, and the pair continued to build on the platform Dearden had established. Glamorgan, despite their earlier breakthroughs, found it difficult to dislodge Pettini, whose experience shone through. Lukas Carey, though expensive in patches, continued to pose a threat with his pace and bounce, while Andrew Salter tried to tie down the scoring with his accurate left-arm spin. The Welsh county's bowlers, however, struggled to maintain consistent pressure as the pitch flattened out under the floodlights.

Pettini reached his own well-deserved hundred just before the close of play, guiding Leicestershire past the 400-run mark. They declared their innings at 415 for 7, giving their bowlers a brief spell at Glamorgan's openers before stumps. The declaration was a clear statement of intent, aiming to put Glamorgan under pressure immediately. Glamorgan faced a tricky 10-over period under lights, which proved challenging. Sam Northeast and Nick Selman weathered the initial storm, but the Foxes' new ball bowlers, led by Chris Wright, made them play at everything. Glamorgan ended the day on 28 for 1, having lost Selman cheaply, caught at slip off a superb delivery from Gavin Griffiths. Northeast (15 not out) and Marnus Labuschagne (8 not out) will resume tomorrow, with Glamorgan still trailing by a substantial 387 runs. The match remains finely poised, with Leicestershire holding a clear advantage due to Dearden's heroics and Pettini's late flourish, but Glamorgan will be hoping their strong batting line-up can respond on what appears to be a good batting surface. The early wickets on day two will be crucial for both sides as the contest heats up in this Championship clash.

The 27 - year - old former England youth international , who left Chelsea in 2018, has now joined Sunderland on a permanent deal, seeking regular first-team football after a loan spell at Everton. His career began at a youth academy, and he represented England at various youth levels before making his senior debut.

It 's reported he had the idea at 2 pm and after a whirl of speculation , and a few changes of venue , tickets went on sale for Koko in Camden at 7 pm . Crowds waited hours in the cold before Kanye eventually took to the stage about 1.20am . The anticipation was palpable, a testament to the artist's magnetic pull, even amidst the late hour and biting chill. When the lights dimmed and the first notes rang out, a collective roar erupted from the packed Koko, transforming the long wait into a forgotten inconvenience. Kanye, known for his electrifying, often unpredictable, live shows, launched into a powerful set, blending tracks from his expansive discography with new material. The energy was electric, a raw connection between the artist and his dedicated fanbase.

The night, however, held even more surprises for the Camden crowd. Mid-set, the atmosphere intensified as London's grime royalty emerged. First, the iconic Skepta exploded onto the stage, sending the venue into a frenzy with a blistering performance, solidifying the long-rumored collaboration. The crowd was already in raptures when JME joined his brother, delivering a high-octane display that further elevated the sky-high energy. The sight of these titans sharing the stage was pure magic, a cultural convergence. Adding to the international flavour, Vic Mensa, a close collaborator of Kanye’s, also made a surprise appearance, showcasing his distinct flow. The mix of long-time fans and eager newcomers savoured every second of the historic, unconventional concert. It was a chaotic, brilliant night that cemented Kanye's reputation for pushing boundaries and delivering unforgettable experiences, leaving an indelible mark on London's music scene and the fervent crowd who braved the elements for a truly special performance.

It was the first time the Commonwealth gold medallist had fought in front of his home crowd at a packed Meadowbank . " I did n't think it would be as quick as that , " Taylor told BBC Scotland . " This boy is very special , " said manager Barry McGuigan . We 've got to take the right fights at the right time . " The Hungarian Mate came into the contest with an impressive record with 17 wins in his 22 previous fights , but it was evident from the first bell that Mate was in for a tough night. Taylor, known for his explosive power and intelligent boxing, wasted no time in asserting his dominance. He moved fluidly, cutting off the ring and landing sharp, accurate jabs that quickly reddened Mate’s face. The Edinburgh crowd, already buzzing with anticipation, roared with every connection. Taylor’s southpaw stance and powerful left hand proved particularly problematic for the Hungarian, who struggled to find his rhythm or land anything significant in return.

Within the first minute, a blistering combination from Taylor – a left hook followed by a straight right – sent Mate stumbling backward into the ropes. The Commonwealth gold medallist, sensing an early finish, pressed home his advantage with relentless aggression. Mate showed commendable resilience, trying to clinch and weather the storm, but Taylor's precision and volume of punches were overwhelming. Just past the midway point of the opening round, a perfectly timed left uppercut from Taylor snapped Mate’s head back, followed by a crunching right hook that sent the visitor to the canvas.

The referee immediately began his count as Mate struggled to regain his footing, his eyes glazed. Although he managed to clamber upright at the count of nine, his legs were clearly unsteady, and the referee wisely waved off the contest, deeming him unable to continue. The official time of the stoppage was just 2 minutes and 10 seconds of the first round, a truly emphatic and devastating performance from the Prestonpans pugilist. The packed Meadowbank Arena erupted in a deafening roar, a standing ovation for their hometown hero.

After the fight, a beaming Taylor soaked in the adulation of the crowd, acknowledging their support. Speaking to BBC Scotland later, he reflected on the win, reiterating his surprise at the swiftness of the victory. "I came here expecting a tough fight, maybe a few rounds to get warmed up, but I caught him clean early and just went for it. The support from the fans was incredible, it really spurred me on."

Manager Barry McGuigan, the legendary former world champion, watched on with immense satisfaction. "Josh showed tonight exactly why we believe he's destined for greatness," McGuigan told reporters. "His power, his speed, his ring intelligence – it's all there. He handled the pressure of fighting at Meadowbank in front of his home fans perfectly. This was a statement win, a clear message to the super-lightweight division. We're not rushing anything, as I said before, we've got to take the right fights at the right time to develop him properly. But he's learning and improving with every bout. We'll sit down, review this performance, and plan the next step. There are big fights out there for Josh, and he’s ready for the challenges that lie ahead. This performance only confirms that he is truly a very special talent, someone who could go all the way to the top of the sport." The victory marked another significant milestone in Taylor's rapidly ascending professional career, setting the stage for even bigger challenges and proving his pedigree on home soil against a credible opponent, even if the fight itself didn't last long. The buzz around Taylor grew exponentially after this dominant display at Meadowbank, solidifying his status as one of Scotland's most exciting boxing prospects, a true champion in the making, following in the footsteps of previous Commonwealth Games successes.

The Belgian , 24 , who signed from Everton for ¬£75 m , got the winner seven minutes before half - time to add to Henrikh Mkhitaryan 's equaliser after United had fallen behind on 20 minutes . United then lost Juan Mata to injury and Antonio Valencia to a red card . " [ Lukaku 's goal ] is nice for him but not important for me , " said Mourinho . " I told him that what's important is the collective result, the three points, not his personal tally. His goal was crucial, yes, but it came in a game where we faced significant challenges, including going behind, losing Juan Mata to injury, and Antonio Valencia to a red card. These moments test a team's resilience, and I'm pleased with how we fought to get the win, but we must learn from the mistakes that put us in those difficult positions. The injury to Juan Mata is a big concern. He is a key player for us, and his creativity will be missed. We will assess the extent of the injury, but it did not look good. As for Antonio Valencia's red card, it was a moment of indiscipline that he knows was unnecessary. An experienced player should not make such a mistake, leaving his team with ten men and missing the next match. We cannot afford these kinds of errors if we want to compete for major honours.

Romelu knows my expectations are high, not just for scoring goals, but for his all-round contribution. I want to see him link up play, press from the front, and be constantly involved in our attacking build-up, not just waiting for chances. Goals are a consequence of doing everything else correctly. He has the potential to be a complete forward for Manchester United, and we will continue to work on all aspects of his game. The team showed character to get the win after so many setbacks, including Henrikh Mkhitaryan's equaliser being cancelled out earlier before we recovered. However, the overall performance was not perfect. We gave them too much space at times and should have been more clinical to finish the game off sooner. We must improve consistently. We take the three points, analyse where we need to get better, and immediately focus on the next challenge. The season is long, and we need every player to maintain focus, discipline, and deliver high-level performances without errors that hurt the team.

The Rhodesian Squadron Royal Air Force plane , based at RAF Wittering , crashed at Holme on 22 November 1940 . Pilot Officer Harold Penketh , from Brighton , did not bail out and died . The Spitfire remains were found after a geophysical survey of the area . It is hoped the recovered parts will be put on public display , offering a poignant reminder of the sacrifices made during World War Two.

Pilot Officer Penketh, aged just 20 at the time of the tragedy, was flying a Supermarine Spitfire Mk IIa, a crucial fighter aircraft during the Battle of Britain and its aftermath. While the exact cause of the crash remains unknown, it is speculated that he may have been attempting to steer his damaged aircraft away from the village of Holme, thus preventing further casualties on the ground, a common act of heroism among pilots of that era. His decision not to bail out, despite the clear danger, underscores the immense courage displayed by so many young men in the face of conflict. Harold Penketh's name is commemorated on the Brighton & Hove War Memorial, serving as a permanent tribute to his ultimate sacrifice.

The archaeological team, working closely with aviation historians and military experts, undertook a meticulous excavation following the successful geophysical survey. This state-of-the-art technique had revealed anomalies beneath the surface, consistent with buried metallic objects, leading them directly to the crash site. Over several weeks, a variety of artefacts were carefully unearthed, including fragments of the Spitfire's engine, sections of the fuselage, instrumentation, and personal effects believed to belong to Pilot Officer Penketh. Each piece recovered tells a part of the story, shedding light on the intensity of aerial combat and the grim reality faced by those defending the nation's skies.

The ongoing conservation efforts aim to stabilise and preserve these precious relics. Plans are underway to create an exhibit, potentially at a local museum or a dedicated aviation heritage centre, which will not only showcase the recovered Spitfire components but also tell the personal story of Harold Penketh and the wider context of the Rhodesian Squadron Royal Air Force's operations from RAF Wittering during the war. This display will serve as an educational resource, ensuring that the bravery of individuals like Penketh and the vital role of the Spitfire in Britain's defence are never forgotten. It will allow visitors to connect directly with a piece of history, understanding the profound human cost of freedom and the legacy of the young pilots who flew from bases like RAF Wittering. The community of Brighton, in particular, has expressed a deep interest in honouring one of their own through this significant historical recovery and memorial. The ultimate goal is to provide a fitting and lasting tribute to Pilot Officer Harold Penketh and all who served.

Kathryn Trussler's sculptures are fashioned from consumer waste including artificial turf and polystyrene.
Her exhibition, at Elysium Gallery from 19 May, was sparked by some unusual finds on Swansea's beach.
Ms Trussler said her work intended to make people question using non-biodegradable substances for fleeting purposes like packaging.
"The inspiration came from what I thought were just a simple pile of pebbles," she added.
"But when I looked closer I realised they were made of old, weathered expanding foam and, descending in size, they stacked on top of each other like the mass produced 'Zen stones' canvases you find at the doctor's or at a motel."

Rehtaeh Parsons, 17, of Nova Scotia, killed herself in April after being taunted over a photo of her alleged rape by four boys, her mother has said.
Two 18-year-old men were arrested on Thursday in connection with the photograph.
The men, who have not been named, will be prosecuted in a juvenile court.
"We hope that today's arrests help the community to heal," Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP) Chief Superintendent Roland Wells of the Halifax district said in a statement on Thursday evening.
"A young girl has died in what was a tragic set of circumstances. We all need to reflect on how we as a community can come together in Rehtaeh's memory and see what we can do to work together to support our youth."
One of the men was charged with two counts of distribution of child pornography, the other with one count each of making child pornography and distribution of child pornography.
The RCMP said the names of the accused would not be released because they were youths at the time of the alleged offence, and warned Halifax residents who believe they know the identities of the accused not to release them on penalty of prosecution, nor to take vigilante action.
According to Rehtaeh's mother Leah Parsons, the Nova Scotia teen went to a party in 2011, when she was 15, and became inebriated after drinking vodka.
The girl told her parents that while she was heavily intoxicated, she was raped by four boys, and someone took a photograph of it.
The photograph was circulated online, and soon her schoolmates began taunting her over the photograph. The bullying was incessant, her mother said.
"She was never left alone," Ms Parsons told CBC News in April after Rehtaeh's suicide.
"Her friends turned against her, people harassed her, boys she didn't know started texting her and Facebooking asking her to have sex with them since she had had sex with their friends. It just never stopped."
Rehtaeh died in April in hospital, several days after attempting suicide.
Police at first said they did not have grounds to make any arrests in connection with the alleged rape or the photograph. The investigation was reopened in April after police said they received new information.

PwC 's annual survey shows that just 37 % think the economy will improve in 2015 , down from 44 % last year . Perhaps unsurprisingly , Russia 's bosses have gone from the most confident to the least , due to problems caused by sanctions and the falling oil price . In the UK , concern had risen sharply about the availability of talent . The number of chief executives concerned about the availability of key skills had risen sharply. This growing talent crunch in the UK, as revealed by the PwC survey, is seen as a significant threat to growth and competitiveness. Many UK businesses report struggling to find and retain staff with essential digital and technical competencies, leading to increased investment in upskilling existing workforces and a focus on attracting international talent where possible.

In contrast to the UK's talent focus, business leaders in Germany and France voiced different primary concerns. German CEOs, while relatively more optimistic than their French counterparts, were predominantly worried about global demand slowdowns and geopolitical instability impacting their export-heavy industries. The eurozone's tepid recovery also cast a shadow, with concerns over deflation and consumer spending remaining high. In France, chief executives were more preoccupied with domestic regulatory burdens and the need for structural reforms to stimulate economic activity. Confidence levels remained subdued across both nations, reflecting a cautious European outlook amidst ongoing economic uncertainties and the lingering effects of the debt crisis.

Globally, the PwC survey of over 1,300 CEOs highlighted a universal shift towards caution. Beyond Russia's unique challenges stemming from sanctions and falling oil prices, and the UK's specific talent woes, the overall sentiment was one of strategic retrenchment. Only 37% of chief executives globally expected economic improvement, down from 44%. This marked decline underscores a pervasive sense of uncertainty across various regions, influenced by factors ranging from commodity price volatility to geopolitical tensions. CEOs indicated a greater focus on operational efficiency, cost control, and organic growth strategies, with less appetite for aggressive expansion. Investment in innovation, particularly digital technologies, emerged as a key priority to build resilience and secure competitive advantage in a volatile global market.

Six policemen died in a gunfight during an operation to evict the farmers from land they had been occupying . Eleven protesters were also killed . The deaths deepened political tensions in Paraguay and were used by congress to oust the left - wing President Fernando Lugo . Four men received sentences of between 18 and 30 years in jail This tragic incident, which unfolded on June 15, 2012, at the Campos Morumbi estate in Curuguaty, became widely known as the Curuguaty Massacre. The land in question was fiercely disputed, with landless farmers claiming it as state property intended for agrarian reform. The subsequent judicial process was highly controversial; human rights organizations and international observers heavily criticized the trial of the eleven farmers, alleging a lack of due process and insufficient evidence linking them to the police deaths.

The massacre provided the immediate catalyst for the Paraguayan congress to orchestrate a rapid impeachment of President Fernando Lugo. His swift removal, days after the killings, was seen as a politically motivated move to reverse his land reform agenda. Several regional governments, including MERCOSUR and UNASUR, condemned Lugo's ouster as a 'parliamentary coup,' leading to Paraguay's temporary suspension from these blocs.

Despite the initial convictions handed down in 2016, a major turning point occurred in July 2017. The Supreme Court of Justice of Paraguay annulled the sentences against the eleven convicted farmers, including the four, citing a lack of concrete evidence and procedural errors. This landmark decision led to their immediate release, marking a complex legal saga that underscored the deep-seated land conflicts and political polarization in Paraguay. The Curuguaty case remains a poignant symbol of the ongoing struggle for land rights and justice in the nation's history.

The Official Charts Company says it is the first time in history an artist has taken the top two chart positions with brand new songs . The singer said he was " incredibly chuffed " by the success . " Both tracks mean a huge amount to me so it really is amazing to see them go to the top of the chart together . " Source : Official Charts Company Sheeran 's comeback follows a " gap year " where he removed himself from social media and touring to travel the world and "see more than the inside of a studio or a hotel room ". His decision to step away from the limelight, though temporary, allowed him to reconnect with his roots and find fresh inspiration, a move that has clearly paid dividends with this unprecedented chart dominance. The Official Charts Company confirmed that this double-top entry is a truly historic moment, reflecting the immense anticipation for new material from the globally adored singer-songwriter.

The two tracks, 'Shape of You' and 'Castle on the Hill', showcase different facets of Sheeran's musical artistry. 'Shape of You' is a catchy, rhythmic pop offering with a subtle dance influence, while 'Castle on the Hill' is a nostalgic, anthemic ode to his upbringing in Framlingham, Suffolk, capturing the essence of small-town life and youthful friendships. The contrasting styles demonstrate his versatility and broad appeal, ensuring both critical acclaim and commercial success. The immediate impact of both songs highlights the power of a well-executed comeback.

This phenomenal achievement comes amidst a highly competitive music landscape. While other artists like Drake have consistently dominated the charts in recent years with their own string of hits, Sheeran's simultaneous one-two punch is a unique feat that underscores his singular talent and dedicated fanbase. His return has undoubtedly revitalised the UK charts, bringing a fresh wave of excitement and setting a new benchmark for chart performance.

Upon hearing the news, Sheeran reiterated his gratitude to fans, acknowledging the hard work and personal significance behind both tracks. "It's been a long time coming," he remarked, referring to the creative process during his sabbatical. "To have both songs resonate so deeply with people, especially 'Castle on the Hill' which is so personal, means the world to me." The Official Charts Company added that the sheer volume of streams and downloads for both tracks was staggering, easily surpassing all other entries. This unparalleled success solidifies Sheeran's position as one of the most influential and popular musicians of his generation, proving that a hiatus can sometimes be the perfect catalyst for even greater triumphs. His ability to connect with listeners on such an intimate level, coupled with his undeniable songwriting prowess, continues to set him apart in the global music scene. Fans eagerly await further announcements regarding his forthcoming album, which is now poised to become one of the biggest releases of the year. The initial reception to these two singles suggests that his "gap year" has only amplified his creative output, leading to an even more refined and impactful sound. The music world is watching closely as Sheeran continues to break new ground and redefine chart history, demonstrating an enduring appeal that transcends genres and generations.

From Winston Churchill's infamous visit to Belfast in 1912 to a 1963 Viking invasion re-enactment in a County Down fishing town, as well as tales of tourism, industrial heritage and sport, a dazzling mosaic of Ulster life is pieced together in unseen archive footage.
Hundreds of unique films have been released to the public to view online for free after the British Film Institute (BFI) unlocked its archive as part of a major history project, From Britain On Film.
Royal visits and Lord Mayor's shows are documented in the collection, as is the tale of Churchill's appearance in Belfast when he addressed an audience of nationalists in Celtic Park and gave his support to Home Rule.
There are also dozens of travelogues that were used to sell Northern Ireland to tourists in Great Britain and the United States, helping to boost tourism in the years before the Troubles.
And in sport, the 1930 Ulster Tourist Trophy race held at the Ards circuit in County Down is captured on camera. The event attracted thousands of spectators and commanded the attention of the motorsport world.
The real gems, however, are found in the footage of ordinary people doing extraordinary things.
Films of people at work in the spinning mills and constructing the M1 at Stockman's Lane in Belfast shows Northern Ireland's industry at its booming best.
Another film captures the first time Northern Ireland hosted the World Ploughing Championships, and fittingly it is a local man who takes the title.
The colour footage from the 1959 competition in Armoy, County Antrim, shows Lawrence McMillan's crowning moment as he gets his hands on the Golden Plough.
But perhaps most revealing of all is a 1938 recording of the Royal Victoria Hospital in Belfast.
It gives a rare glimpse into the casualty department and operating theatres as they were then, 10 years before the foundation of the National Health Service.
While medicine has advanced considerably in the eight decades since then, some aspects of healthcare in Northern Ireland appear to remain unchanged - the film ends with an appeal from the chairman of the hospital's management board to reduce waiting lists.
Francis Jones, of Northern Ireland Screen, which gathered much of the footage, said the aim of the project was to preserve delicate film that could otherwise be lost.
"There is a pure nostalgia value to film. It's different to reading a textbook or history book," he added.
"To actually see the film has that kind of visceral appeal and really strikes a chord with people."
The full From Britain On Film archive can be viewed at the BFI Player.

North Ronaldsay Primary School's single classroom will be kept on standby from August as Teigan Scott, 12, moves to secondary in Kirkwall.
Orkney's most northerly island only has a population of about 50 people.
Orkney Islands Council said the school would be brought back into use if more families with young children moved to the island.
The building is also used by community groups.
Island residents have blamed poor transport links for the lack of young families.
Teigan told the BBC she was looking forward to moving on to secondary but worried for the future of her former school.
"I am excited to go up to the bigger school," she said.
"But I have a tiny little drop of sadness because the school will be closing and the island might fall apart."
Councillor Kevin Woodbridge said the population on North Ronaldsay had halved since he arrived in 1977.
He said: "It's very sad but it demonstrates the decline on the island that has led to this.
"When I came here there were 17 people at the school and 127 on the island, now we have 50 to 60 people.
"The quality of life on the island can be improved considerably."
Billy Muir, chairman of the community council, said the loss of the school's only pupil was "a very serious blow for the community and no doubt will have a knock-on effect".
He said: "We need new housing to be built and to get new families in. You want a number of kids in the school, not just one.
"Higher speed broadband is needed too.
"There's no point painting a good picture, we have to be realistic. Hopefully this highlights our problem."

Ninety - three of the retailer 's 125 stores will close , with the rest remaining open while buyers are sought . If administrator KPMG can not find buyers , the remaining stores will also shut . The chain employed 1,658 people . The chain was sold to Greybull Capital last year by supermarket Morrisons , which has said it would offer jobs to ex - My Local staff . It has struggled since being acquired by private equity firm Greybull Capital in September 2015. The chain, formerly Morrisons M Local, was sold off by the supermarket giant as part of a strategic shift away from smaller convenience formats to focus on its larger superstores. At the time of the sale, Morrisons provided significant financial support to Greybull Capital, including a loan of up to £25 million, to help stabilize the business and facilitate its turnaround. However, the investment proved insufficient to reverse its fortunes in an increasingly competitive market dominated by established players like Tesco Express and Sainsbury's Local, as well as discounters.

The challenges faced by the former Morrisons' M Local stores under Greybull Capital’s stewardship were multifaceted. High operating costs, coupled with intense price competition and shifts in consumer shopping habits, created a difficult trading environment. Despite efforts to rebrand and reposition the stores as ‘My Local’, aiming for a community-focused offering, the chain failed to gain significant traction or achieve sustainable profitability. The decision to appoint KPMG as administrators came after a period of intense financial pressure, leaving no viable path forward without significant restructuring.

KPMG's immediate priority has been to manage the closure of the 93 unprofitable stores and to seek buyers for the remaining 32. Sources close to the administration process indicate that finding a single buyer for the remaining portfolio might be challenging, suggesting that individual or smaller clusters of stores could be sold off to other retailers or convenience store operators. The closure process will unfortunately result in the loss of a significant number of the 1,658 jobs, though Morrisons' proactive offer to re-employ former My Local staff, where possible, provides some relief to those affected. This gesture by Morrisons highlights its ongoing commitment, having initially established the convenience arm and then divested it.

The collapse of My Local underscores the difficulties even established players face in the convenience sector. For Greybull Capital, this represents a significant setback, adding to their mixed portfolio of investments. The future of the remaining 32 stores hinges entirely on KPMG’s ability to secure buyers within a reasonable timeframe, failing which, they too will inevitably shut, marking the complete disappearance of the My Local brand from the high street, less than a year after its high-profile launch under Greybull.

Lord Advocate Frank Mulholland also told MSPs that a fatal accident inquiry would be held into the death.

"It has been 19 weeks since Sheku's death and the family hope the Lord Advocate can provide them with the truth of what happened, because without that they know there can be no justice."
