Star Randel-Hanson killed Derick Marney, 70, at a flat in Vernon Terrace, Brighton, in May 2015.
He broke down and confessed to the murder 10 days later he went to tarot reader Jayne Braiden on Brighton seafront.
She alerted police but was told it was a "non-emergency" so she waited an hour with the killer for an officer to come.
Ms Braiden told BBC Radio 5 Live: "By the time we got to the devil card he broke down and started crying.
"It's the first time I've dealt with murder before. It was a shock but you have to be professional and I needed to keep him calm."
Mr Marney died from a six-inch (15cm) stab wound to his side, which punctured his vital organs.
Sussex Police said it was "not clear" what motivated Randel-Hanson - who was jailed for life on 9 May - to carry out the murder.
After gaining the defendant's trust, Ms Braiden asked him whether she could go outside to call the police. He agreed.
She said: "I explained [to the 999 operator] I was a tarot reader and told her a man had confessed to murder.
"She told me it was a non-priority call and I needed to ring the non-emergency number.
"Unfortunately they didn't believe me, but I'm not surprised at that."
She said she then bought Randel-Hanson a drink from a shop next door and waited 55 minutes for police to arrive.
"I asked him if it was ok if I took notes... I took names, places, where he had been stabbed and where the body was," she said.
"I didn't ask him why, and to be fair I don't think he wanted to talk to me about that.
"We joked about the time it took the police to come.
"He was getting tense at that point as I was not only looking for police through the glass doors, he was as well."
Sussex Police later admitted the call had been given the wrong level of priority.
A spokesman said it has been discussed with the call handler concerned and "suitable advice was given".

The swoon weighed on US markets , offsetting gains in financial and energy stocks . The tech - heavy Nasdaq index fell 113.84 points or 1.80%% to 6,207.92 . The broader S&P 500 dipped 2.02 points or 0.08 % to 2,431.77 , while the Dow Jones edged up 89.44 points , rising 0.42 % to 21,271.97 . US markets had seen limited movement earlier this week . The sharp downturn in the tech-heavy Nasdaq was largely attributed to burgeoning political uncertainty in Washington, particularly stemming from recent developments in the ongoing FBI investigation into the administration. This created a cautious sentiment among investors, leading to a significant sell-off in technology stocks, which disproportionately impacted the Nasdaq's performance. In contrast, the Dow Jones Industrial Average, with its lesser exposure to the technology sector, managed to post a gain, buoyed by strength in its financial and industrial components. The S&P 500's slight dip reflected the mixed performance across various sectors, where some gains, notably in energy and financials, partially offset the broader tech-led decline. Investors are now closely scrutinizing political headlines, as they appear to be driving market movements more significantly than economic data or corporate earnings. This shift in focus underscores a growing investor apprehension regarding potential political fallout. Across the Atlantic, the UK's FTSE 100 also experienced a modest decline, mirroring the global risk-off sentiment. The overall market mood indicates that political risks are increasingly weighing on US equity valuations, prompting a re-evaluation of portfolio strategies as the week concludes.

Police were called to a break - in at a house in the Shiregreen area of the city on Monday . The victim is in " a stable condition in hospital after suffering injuries during the violent break-in. South Yorkshire Police are investigating the incident, which occurred just after midnight. Detective Inspector Paul Wilson, leading the inquiry, said: 'This was a distressing incident for the homeowner. We are appealing for anyone who saw anything suspicious in the Shiregreen area around that time to come forward. Any information, no matter how small, could be crucial to our investigation. We are committed to bringing those responsible for this break to justice.' Officers have conducted house-to-house inquiries and are reviewing CCTV footage from the surrounding area as part of their ongoing efforts to trace the offenders.

Andreea Cristea is the fifth victim of the attack on 22 March , in which Khalid Masood drove into crowds on Westminster Bridge then stabbed a policeman to death , before being shot dead himself . Ms Cristea , 31 , who was on holiday with boyfriend Andrei Burnaz , had been in hospital since the attack . It has emerged that Mr Burnaz had been planning to propose during the day out . A family statement confirmed Ms Cristea , who was an architect , had died on Thursday . The architect, who had been visiting London from Romania, was thrown into the River Thames during the rampage by Khalid Masood. She was rescued from the water but had suffered catastrophic head injuries and a severe lung infection, remaining in critical condition for weeks at St Thomas' Hospital. Her family, including her parents and sister, had maintained a constant vigil at her bedside, desperately hoping for her recovery, until her tragic passing.

Mr Burnaz, who sustained a fractured foot in the attack and has since undergone surgery, has spoken emotionally about the terrifying moments after they were hit and his desperate search for Andreea amidst the chaos. He described seeing Ms Cristea disappear into the water after being struck by the vehicle, and his frantic efforts to locate her before she was pulled out by rescuers. The couple, originally from Constanța, Romania, were on a romantic trip, and the revelation that Mr Burnaz had intended to propose adds a profoundly tragic layer to their story, highlighting the dreams and future abruptly stolen by the act of terror.

Ms Cristea's death tragically brings the total number of fatalities directly resulting from Khalid Masood's attack to five. The other victims were US tourist Kurt Cochran, retired window cleaner Leslie Rhodes, and mother-of-two Aysha Frade, all of whom were struck on Westminster Bridge, along with PC Keith Palmer, the brave officer stabbed to death by Masood at the gates of the Palace of Westminster. The attack, which stunned the world, transformed a bustling London landmark into a scene of unimaginable horror and grief.

Tributes have poured in for Andreea, remembering her as a vibrant, talented architect with a promising future. The Romanian Ambassador to the UK expressed deep sorrow, conveying the shared grief of the Romanian community for her loss. Her tragic passing is a stark reminder of the global reach of such violence, impacting individuals from diverse backgrounds who were simply enjoying a day out in a major capital. The investigation into Masood’s motives and potential associates continues, but the devastating human cost of his actions, epitomized by Ms Cristea and Mr Burnaz, remains the most poignant legacy. London, a city known for its enduring spirit and resilience, mourns its lost, but remains united against the hatred that seeks to divide it.

Britain 's world heavyweight champion apologised last month for a video he posted online containing homophobic , sexist and anti - Semitic comments . But ex - champion Klitschko , who fights Fury in Manchester on 9 July , said : " I was in shock at his statements . " When I heard about the video, I found it incredibly disturbing," the Ukrainian fighter continued, clearly upset. "As a professional athlete, you have a responsibility to be a role model. To use your platform for such hateful rhetoric, especially anti-Semitic comments that evoke dark periods of history, is simply unacceptable. It goes against everything sport should represent." Klitschko, himself from a nation that suffered immensely during World War II, expressed deep concern about the impact such statements could have.

Fury’s controversial remarks had drawn widespread condemnation across Britain, leading to calls for his license to be revoked. His anti-Semitic tirade, in which he claimed "Zionist, Jewish people... own all the banks, all the palaces, all the world," caused profound offence, echoing historical prejudices. His previous sexist and homophobic comments also resurfaced, painting a picture of ingrained bigotry. The Campaign Against Antisemitism, a prominent UK watchdog, was particularly vocal, calling for decisive action against the British boxer. They emphasized the danger of hateful speech from high-profile athletes, especially when it mirrors rhetoric associated with figures like Hitler, stressing the need for public figures to grasp the gravity of their words. Klitschko added, "This isn't just about boxing anymore. This is about basic human decency and respect." He stressed that while the fight was imminent, Fury’s actions had transcended the sport, raising serious questions about a champion's values. The immense backlash forced Fury to issue an apology, which many found insincere, only fueling the controversy.

The visitors closed on 293 - 9 at the end of day three , with a lead of 260 . Jacques Rudolph 's wait for a first Championship hundred in 2016 continued as he chopped onto his stumps for 56 . Earlier , Essex had been bowled out for 319 , with Craig Meschede ( 5 - 84 ) taking his first five - wicket haul in first-class cricket for Glamorgan. His accurate seam bowling ripped through the Essex middle order, claiming the crucial scalps of Simon Harmer and Neil Wagner as Essex were dismissed for 319. Earlier, Alastair Cook had made a patient 90, but Meschede's spell truly restricted Essex.

Glamorgan began their second innings with a 26-run deficit. Openers Nick Selman (41) and Jacques Rudolph built a steady platform. Rudolph, despite his eventual dismissal, looked largely untroubled for much of his 125-ball stay, striking seven boundaries. His uncharacteristic lapse saw him drag a delivery from Jamie Porter onto his stumps, ending his aspirations of a century. His departure at 110 for 2 brought Marnus Labuschagne (28) to the crease, who was then trapped lbw by Sam Cook. The Glamorgan middle order faced a testing period. Chris Cooke battled for his 35, and Kiran Carlson added 22, but wickets fell regularly as Essex bowlers exploited the variable bounce. A late cameo from Ryan Thomas, who hit a valuable 18 not out, helped extend the lead as the light faded. The visitors will hope their tailenders can add valuable runs on day four to set Essex a challenging target, with the pitch showing signs of wear and tear, promising more assistance for the spinners. Rudolph's earlier efforts, alongside Meschede's disciplined bowling, have put Glamorgan in a strong position, but the final day promises to be tense. The match remains finely poised, with Glamorgan holding the upper hand thanks to their consistent batting and Meschede's destructive spell.

Logan Murdoch suffered serious injuries in the crash and was not breathing when the Great North Air Ambulance team arrived . Hayley Murdoch , 29 , and Sheila Dixon , 71 , both from Carlisle , died following the collision at Newby Cross in 2016 . Dr Laura Duffy called Logan , years after that harrowing day, to marvel at his incredible journey back to health. She vividly recalled the scene at Newby Cross, describing it as one of the most challenging she had ever encountered. Logan had been clinically dead, but through the swift, coordinated efforts of the emergency services – the first responders, paramedics, and the air ambulance crew – he was resuscitated at the roadside. He was then airlifted to the Royal Victoria Infirmary in Newcastle in a critical condition, placed in an induced coma, and remained there for several weeks, fighting for his life. His family, already reeling from the devastating loss of Hayley Murdoch and Sheila Dixon, braced themselves for the worst, enduring agonizing days and nights by his bedside.

Against all odds, Logan began a slow, arduous recovery. Dr Duffy recounted the initial prognosis, which had been bleak, suggesting severe brain damage and long-term disability were highly probable. Yet, Logan’s resilience and determination, coupled with exceptional medical care, defied these expectations. His rehabilitation was extensive, involving months of physiotherapy, speech therapy, and psychological support to help him come to terms with the traumatic event and the profound grief of losing his mother and grandmother. The call from Dr Duffy was a poignant reminder of how close he came to joining them. She told him that his survival was nothing short of miraculous, a testament to the life-saving work done in those critical moments at the crash site near Carlisle. Logan, now a vocal advocate for the Great North Air Ambulance, often reflects on that day, acknowledging that without their rapid response, he would not be here today to share his story or remember his beloved Hayley Murdoch and Sheila Dixon. The scars, both physical and emotional, remain, but so does an immense gratitude for the second chance at life he received.

Stefan Appleton , 18 , was with friends when he was attacked in Nightingale Park in Islington on 10 June last year . The killer stabbed him with the 25 in ( 63 cm ) serrated blade after leaping off a stolen moped , the Old Bailey heard . The 17 - year - old , who can not be named due to his age , was cleared of murder . He will be sentenced on 21 April . Mr Appleton , a popular and bright teenager, was an avid football fan and a beloved son and brother. His death sent shockwaves through the Islington community, leaving his family and friends devastated. He was described by those who knew him as a joyful and kind-hearted individual with a promising future ahead of him. The brutal nature of the attack, carried out in a public park, deeply rattled local residents and intensified concerns about knife crime among young people.

The Metropolitan Police launched a comprehensive investigation, meticulously gathering evidence and tracking down the perpetrator. Detectives worked tirelessly to piece together the events leading up to the fatal stabbing. The court heard how the assailant, riding a stolen moped, had pursued Stefan before cornering him in Nightingale Park, close to the area often referred to as the Red Pitch, a popular local recreation spot. The ferocity of the attack, involving a large serrated blade, was a key focus of the prosecution’s case.

During the trial at the Old Bailey, the prosecution argued that the defendant had demonstrated a clear intent to cause serious harm, if not death. However, the defence presented arguments challenging the specific intent required for a murder conviction, leading to the jury’s decision to clear the 17-year-old of murder, finding him guilty of manslaughter instead. This verdict, while acknowledging the defendant’s responsibility for Stefan’s death, has been met with mixed emotions by Stefan’s family, who had campaigned tirelessly for justice. They issued a statement expressing their profound grief and the permanent void left by Stefan’s passing, but also reiterated their commitment to advocating for an end to knife violence.

The sentencing hearing on 21 April will determine the consequences for the teenager who took Stefan’s life. The case has highlighted the urgent need for interventions to prevent similar tragedies and to address the root causes of youth violence in London. Stefan Appleton’s legacy, though tragically cut short, continues to serve as a poignant reminder of the devastating impact of knife crime on individuals, families, and communities like Islington.

Lachlan returns to the Murdoch empire as co-chairman of News Corp and 21st Century Fox, having previously stood back to focus on his own businesses.
Meanwhile, younger son James was appointed co-chief operating officer at 21st Century Fox.
After the phone hacking scandal, James quit as executive chairman of News International in 2012.
News Corp is one of the world's biggest media organisations, and owns newspaper titles The Times, Sun, and the Wall Street Journal.
News Corp split from 21st Century Fox in 2013. The business owns broadcaster Fox News in the US and British Sky Broadcasting in the UK.
Rupert Murdoch, who went through a high-profile split with wife Wendi Deng last year, said Lachlan was a "talented executive" with a "rich" knowledge of the business.
Lachlan will report to Chase Carey, chief executive at 21st Century Fox.
Rupert said: "I am very pleased he is returning to a leadership role at the company, where he will look closely with me, Chase, James and rest of the board of directors to drive continued growth for years to come."
He also said he was "pleased" to promote James into the "important role".
There is reportedly no new role for the third sibling, Elisabeth Murdoch, however, who sought to distance herself from James after the phone hacking scandal.

6 October 2016 Last updated at 16:36 BST More than 500 students in South Africa have joined nationwide protests over rising university fees, according to reports monitored by BBC Africa, continuing a movement that began earlier this October.

The Caerau hill fort near Ely is thought to have been occupied from the 5th Century BC by the Silurian tribe . A dig last year involving 1,000 people found its use may have been far more extensive and continuous than previously understood, serving as a vital strategic stronghold for the Silurian tribe for centuries. The ambitious project, led by renowned archaeologist Professor Olly Davis, was a testament to community archaeology, involving 1,000 dedicated volunteers last year who unearthed compelling evidence. Discoveries included sophisticated defensive structures, extensive domestic dwellings, and a wealth of Iron Age artefacts, painting a vivid picture of a thriving, resilient community that played a pivotal role in the Silurians' resistance against Roman expansion in South Wales. This remarkable dig has significantly reshaped our understanding of this historically important site, demonstrating its enduring significance not just as a fort, but as a vibrant centre of life and culture in ancient South Wales.

Up to 40,000 people and 140 bands took part in the march, which is the largest loyal order demonstration in Northern Ireland.
Three people have been arrested for public order offences.
The event began with a parade around the city's historic walls and was followed by a wreath laying ceremony at the War Memorial in the Diamond.
A religious service was also held in St Columb's Cathedral.
PSNI Supt Mark McEwan praised all sides for working together to ensure the parade was peaceful.
"There haven't been any problems today at all, the operation has been a success," he said.
"Everyone seems to have been enjoying a good day out. The feeling and atmosphere in the city is one of festivity."
Jim Brownlee, governor of the Apprentice Boys of Derry, said the emphasis within the Apprentice Boys was on respect.
"That's still down to every member of this association especially when we're on parade and in the public domain," he said.
"We want people to respect this parade and we want the people on parade to respect the people who will either be watching it or commenting upon it."
A pageant re-enacting the Siege of Derry took place ahead of the start of the main parade.

Armed troops are already being deployed to protect key locations such as Buckingham Palace, Downing Street and embassies to free up police officers.
It comes after the bomb attack at Manchester Arena on Monday which killed 22 people, some as young as eight.
London mayor Sadiq Khan said security experts were advising event organisers.
He said there was "no reason to be alarmed or to panic, this is a prudent course to take".
Bomber 'likely' not acting alone
Manchester attack: The next steps for police and MI5
The mayor added he was in close contact with Met Police Commissioner Cressida Dick and the force had assured him they have all the resources they need.
The decision to replace police officers with soldiers at key public locations was taken at a meeting of the government's emergency Cobra committee on Tuesday.
After the announcement the national security threat level was raised to critical and the Palace of Westminster shut to the public.
All tours and events due to take place there have been cancelled with immediate effect.
A man with a knife was arrested outside Buckingham Palace earlier, shortly before the Queen was driven along the Mall. The Met has said the incident is not terror-related.
The FA Cup final between Arsenal and Chelsea takes place at Wembley on Saturday - the final day of the Chelsea Flower Show.
Commander Jane Connors, leading the London policing operation, said: "We will do all we can to protect the capital at this unsettling time. All our work is designed to make our city as hostile an environment as possible for terrorists to plan and operate."
Other measures being taken include an increase in armed officers to provide support for uniformed and undercover officers trying to spot people carrying out "hostile reconnaissance" and other criminal activity in London.
The tactic is "based on extensive research into the psychology of criminals and what undermines their activities", the force said.
There will also be an increase in the use of stop and search, vehicle check points and number plate recognition technology.
"The reality is we must be prepared to be able to respond to and deal with armed and deadly attackers, so we must be in a position to respond with firearms officers who will use force to stop those attackers in their aim," added Ms Connors.

In 2014 , Kim Lennon said the smuggling of drugs was rife at Lewes Prison and its wings " resembled a war zone " . She was dismissed earlier this week following disciplinary proceedings but said she would appeal and had no regrets about speaking out . The Ministry of Justice ( MoJ ) said Ms Lennon was not dismissed for being a whistleblower . ' The Ministry of Justice (MoJ) maintained that Ms Lennon’s dismissal was the result of a comprehensive internal disciplinary process, unconnected to her claims regarding prison conditions. A spokesperson for the MoJ stated that all prison staff are expected to adhere to the highest standards, and where these are not met, disciplinary action will be taken. Citing employee confidentiality, they would not discuss specific details of Ms Lennon's case, but reaffirmed the decision followed a thorough investigation into her conduct, concluding that her actions constituted serious breaches of policy.

Kim Lennon, however, strongly refuted the MoJ’s narrative, asserting that the disciplinary charges against her were a deliberate attempt to discredit her and suppress vital information about the critical state of Lewes Prison. She told reporters that her complaints, made over an extended period, had consistently been met with insufficient action by management. "I reported serious instances of drug dealing, violence, and a complete lack of control, which put both staff and inmates at immense risk," Ms Lennon stated. "Instead of addressing these grave issues, the prison management chose to target me. They wanted to silence anyone brave enough to speak the truth about a system that is failing drastically." She highlighted that the current measures by the Ministry of Justice were clearly insufficient to tackle the deep-rooted problems within the prison.

Ms Lennon’s case brings to light the ongoing challenges faced by the MoJ in managing the escalating problem of drug smuggling and violence within the UK's prison estate. Independent oversight bodies and parliamentary committees have repeatedly raised concerns about the scale of the issue, with reports frequently citing staff shortages, overcrowding, and a lack of resources as contributing factors. Critics argue that the government's response to these systemic failures has been inadequate, leaving frontline officers like Kim Lennon vulnerable when they attempt to expose dangerous realities.

The former officer intends to take her case to an employment tribunal, where she hopes to present evidence not only of wrongful dismissal but also of the dire conditions she witnessed. "My appeal isn't just about my job; it's about exposing the truth for the safety of everyone inside those walls," said Ms Lennon, vowing to continue her fight regardless of the personal cost. She remains steadfast in her belief that the public has a right to know the true state of affairs within their prisons, and that the MoJ must be held accountable for its duty of care. Her legal team is currently preparing the documentation, confident that they can demonstrate that Ms Lennon was unfairly targeted for her whistleblowing activities. The case is expected to draw significant attention to the broader debate around transparency and accountability within the prison system.

That is according to new figures from Northern Ireland Screen , which has provided production funding for the HBO series . The programme , some of which is filmed in Northern Ireland , has been nominated for 24 Emmy awards . Two of those nominations are for Northern Ireland production crew members . Ronan Hill , who won an Emmy in 2012 , has been nominated again for outstanding sound mixing for a drama , while Carla Stronge has been nominated for outstanding casting for the widely acclaimed HBO series. These nominations highlight the immense talent within Northern Ireland's thriving screen industry and underscore the region's growing reputation as a global hub for film and television production. The significant investment from Northern Ireland Screen, an agency dedicated to promoting the film, television, and animation industry, has been instrumental in attracting major international productions like this HBO series to the region. This strategic funding not only provides essential financial support but also helps to develop a robust infrastructure and a highly skilled local workforce, ensuring that Northern Ireland remains a competitive and attractive location for high-profile projects.

The success of the programme, with its impressive 24 Emmy nominations, serves as a powerful testament to the collaborative efforts of international studios and local talent. It demonstrates the depth of expertise available in Northern Ireland, from sound engineering and casting to set design and visual effects. The recognition of Ronan Hill, a multiple Emmy winner, and Carla Stronge, a prominent figure in casting, particularly emphasizes the world-class skills present within the Northern Ireland production community. Their individual achievements reflect the high standards maintained across all facets of the production.

Richard Williams, Chief Executive of Northern Ireland Screen, expressed immense pride in the nominations, stating, "We are absolutely thrilled to see the exceptional work of our local crew members recognised on such a prestigious international stage. Ronan and Carla's nominations are thoroughly deserved and shine a spotlight on the incredible talent pool we have here in Northern Ireland. The continued success of this HBO series, parts of which are meticulously filmed across our beautiful landscapes, showcases the immense value that our region brings to global entertainment. Our commitment to fostering and supporting the indigenous screen industry continues to pay dividends, attracting inward investment, creating jobs, and enhancing our reputation worldwide."

The filming of parts of the series in Northern Ireland has brought considerable economic benefits, including significant spending in the local economy on services, accommodation, and local businesses, as well as providing extensive employment opportunities for hundreds of crew members and ancillary staff. This ongoing success story reinforces the long-term vision of Northern Ireland Screen to build a sustainable and vibrant creative sector, capable of delivering world-class content and competing on the global stage. The upcoming Emmy Awards ceremony will undoubtedly be a moment of great anticipation for everyone involved, particularly for the dedicated Northern Ireland team who have contributed so much to the show's artistic excellence and popular appeal. The impact of such high-profile productions extends beyond mere economic figures, fostering a sense of pride and inspiring the next generation of filmmakers and creative professionals in the region. This pattern of sustained growth and international recognition firmly positions Northern Ireland as a key player in the global entertainment landscape, driven by its unique locations, skilled professionals, and proactive support from organisations like Northern Ireland Screen. The nominations serve as a clear indicator of the high calibre of work being produced and the bright future that lies ahead for the industry in the province.

The suspects are accused of smuggling large quantities of cocaine from Colombia to Europe in sailing boats . Officials said among those arrested is a commander of the Colombian left - wing rebel group , Farc . Police said the suspects were part of a transatlantic drugs ring run by the ' Ndrangheta a powerful organized crime syndicate based in Calabria, southern Italy. This operation highlights the growing partnership between Colombian drug producers, particularly remnant factions associated with the dissolved Farc insurgency, and the sophisticated distribution networks of European mafias. Investigators revealed that the cocaine shipments originated in remote jungle labs in Colombia, often in areas previously controlled by the Farc, who either directly cultivated coca or levied 'taxes' on independent producers for safe passage and processing.

The sailing boats were chosen for their ability to blend in with legitimate maritime traffic, making them less conspicuous than large cargo vessels, and for their capacity to carry substantial loads without attracting undue attention. The routes typically involved crossing the Atlantic, often utilizing strategically located island nations as re-provisioning points before reaching European ports, predominantly in Spain and Portugal, for onward distribution across the continent. This particular bust involved meticulous intelligence gathering over several years, a collaborative effort spanning multiple law enforcement agencies.

A significant breakthrough came with intelligence shared by The US Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA), which had been tracking the cartel's activities and its nexus with various Colombian narco-trafficking groups. Authorities in Colombia and Italy, alongside Europol and other European police forces, executed synchronized raids following the DEA's lead. Among the arrests were key logistical managers in Europe and several suppliers in South America. The Farc commander arrested in Colombia was reportedly a crucial link, responsible for ensuring the quality and quantity of the cocaine supplied and facilitating its transport to coastal rendezvous points. Further investigations are underway in the region, including in areas near Santa Fe, where some of the preliminary processing and logistics for the illicit drug trade are suspected to have taken place, demonstrating the intricate web of this criminal enterprise. The scale of the operation underscores the global reach of organized crime and the persistent challenge posed by the drug trade.

The girl was walking with a woman , aged 55 , when they were suddenly struck by a black Ford Fiesta turning sharply from Lugsmore Lane onto Dunriding Lane. The woman was thrown to the ground, while the girl managed to jump out of the way, narrowly avoiding serious injury. Emergency services were immediately called to the scene.

A report has said uniting council departments with different responsibilities would help improve the town's prospects.
The strategy aims to reduce the number of empty shop units, increase visitors with more public events and reduce antisocial behaviour.
It is being discussed at a council meeting on Wednesday afternoon.
Town centre forum business group chairman Andrew Atkinson welcomed the report and said it could lead to be a "huge turnaround for Wrexham".
The report highlights how one department looks after town centre economic strategy while others deal with cleaning up the streets or looking after licensing and public protection issues although they share a common goal.
It recommends a single group taking forward all issues that tackle town centre improvements.
Mr Atkinson said: "It has got to be action and not words from the council."
He said the authority was taking positive steps with shops' vacancy rates reducing due to more independent shops opening, but he admitted bigger units formerly occupied by multi national firms were "harder to fill".
This month, work started on a ¬£4.5m development at Wrexham's People's Market to incorporate an arts centre.

The statement from the firm came just days after it announced the sale of the Financial Times to Japan 's Nikkei . Pearson said it was in discussions regarding the sale of the Economist but there was " no certainty that this process will lead to a transaction ". This divestment of its print media holdings, including the iconic Financial Times, signals a clear strategic pivot for Pearson. The company, under CEO John Fallon, is increasingly focusing on its global education business, aiming to streamline its portfolio and concentrate resources on digital learning and assessment tools. This marks the end of an era for Pearson as a diversified media conglomerate, aligning with a broader industry trend of specialization.

The potential sale of its 50% stake in the Economist Group, which publishes the influential weekly magazine, presents a more intricate challenge. Unlike the straightforward acquisition of the Financial Times by Japan's Nikkei, the Economist has a unique ownership structure designed to safeguard its editorial independence. A trust holds a significant portion of shares, and a consortium of long-standing family shareholders – including the Rothschilds, Cadburys, and Schroders, alongside Italy's powerful Agnelli family through their investment vehicle Exor – own the remaining stakes. John Elkann, chairman of Exor, had publicly expressed interest in increasing their shareholding, emphasizing their commitment to maintaining the publication's journalistic integrity and distinct ethos.

This inherent complexity, requiring consensus among existing shareholders deeply invested in the Economist's long-term vision, explains Pearson's cautious statement regarding "no certainty." For Pearson, completing these divestitures would solidify its identity as a pure-play education company, allowing it to dedicate all efforts to developing digital learning platforms globally and capitalize on the evolving education sector. These moves underscore the significant redefinition underway in the media and publishing industries.

Zdenko Turtak , who was extradited from Slovakia , had previously admitted rape and grievous bodily harm in the UK. His case, involving serious offences, was heard at Leeds Crown Court where Turtak faced sentencing after his extradition from Slovakia. The judicial process ensured Zdenko Turtak was brought to justice for the crimes committed.

The star of How I Met Your Mother and Gone Girl will host 10 episodes of the variety show for NBC , according to the Hollywood Reporter . Harris called the show , created by British TV presenting duo Ant McPartlin and Declan Donnelly , " a fantastic opportunity to bring a fresh, modern take on the classic variety show format to American audiences. It’s a genre I’ve always loved and respected, and the chance to reinvent it with a team as talented as this, led by the brilliant Ant and Dec, is truly exciting."

Harris, known for his charismatic stage presence and versatile talents—spanning acting, singing, dancing, and even magic—is considered a natural fit for the demanding role. His extensive experience hosting major awards shows like the Academy Awards, Tony Awards, and Emmy Awards has solidified his reputation as a master of ceremonies capable of engaging large audiences with his wit and charm. The new NBC series, which is expected to blend celebrity interviews, musical performances, sketches, games, and audience participation, aims to recreate the magic of live television that has been a hallmark of classic variety shows while infusing it with a contemporary sensibility. This unique blend aligns perfectly with Harris's diverse skill set, promising a show that is both nostalgic and innovative.

The 24 - year - old , who can not be named until he enters his plea , is accused of raping the teenager in the toilets of a bar in Johannesburg . Earlier in the week , the family of the alleged victim said that Mr Mandela , widely believed to be a grandson of the late Nelson Mandela, had been identified to them as the perpetrator. While the 24-year-old cannot be officially named by the media until he enters his plea, the victim's family has expressed their profound distress and called for swift justice. They confirmed that they had reached out to members of the broader Mandela family, including Makaziwe Mandela, for support in this sensitive matter. A spokesperson for the family indicated that they felt a moral obligation from the Mandela lineage, historically associated with fighting for justice, to address the serious allegations. The BBC has learned that while no formal statement has been issued by the Mandela family, sources close to Winnie Madikizela-Mandela's descendants have privately conveyed their deep concern over the incident in Johannesburg and stated they are awaiting the due process of law. The case continues to attract significant public and media interest across South Africa.

Members of Braintree's Dolphin Women's Institute (WI) have stitched some of the town's best-known landmarks including the church and museum.
Each model is about 45cm (18in) tall and was created using a polystyrene or cardboard core with knitting sewn on.
It took nine knitters seven months to complete the seven miniature buildings which will be displayed at the town's museum next month.
The group's vice-president, Elaine Pye, said the project was inspired by a similar one a relative had been involved in knitting in Hertfordshire.
"They knitted their own cottages, but we couldn't really do that so chose some of the town's beautiful iconic buildings," she said.
Mrs Pye put together the polystyrene structures and each knitter got to work, returning after two weeks with their latest knitted piece of church spire or pub frontage.
After much gluing, sewing and additional knitted embellishments, the town finally took shape, brought together with mini woollen market stalls.
The group created models of the town hall, church, Swan pub, library, museum, shopping centre and even the railway station complete with knitted train.
"It really brought everyone together and the response has been amazing," Mrs Pye said.
"So much so that they want to do more, so we think we might knit the Public Gardens next."

A total of 374 employees lost their jobs when Tullis Russell Papermakers, based at Markinch in Fife, went into administration in April 2015.
Each employee received the equivalent of eight weeks' wages in compensation for their loss.
The award follows a judgement from an employment tribunal in Dundee.
Lawyers said that despite the company directors being under an obligation to provide employees with at least 45 days' notice - as more than 100 workers were losing their jobs - this was ignored, meaning each employee was entitled to sue for compensation.
However, acting alone would have meant each affected worker lodging "an extremely complex" and expensive employment tribunal claim, so they made a joint bid.
David Martyn, a senior employment lawyer at Thompsons, the firm that represented the workers, said: "The more notice the workforce have to prepare for these devastating changes, the better they can organise their financial responsibilities to soften the blow.
"This award of compensation will be paid by UK administration service.
"That means that the taxpayer has picked up the tab because company directors have played fast and loose with the rules.
"This has to stop and I believe we need to see more criminal prosecutions of companies that behave this way."
Paul Reilly, Unite branch secretary said: "This is a great result for my members and it goes a long way towards the hurt that happened."

The move follows a rise in the number of oil and gas operators using unmanned aerial systems ( UAS ) to conduct inspections and other offshore tasks . The guidelines were developed by industry and aviation safety experts and UAS operators . They provide comprehensive and clear guidance for safe and efficient UAS operations across the UK offshore energy sector. These guidelines cover critical areas such as operational planning, risk assessment, personnel competency, equipment standards, and emergency response procedures, aiming to standardize practices and significantly enhance overall safety. The increasing use of UAS offers substantial benefits for the industry, including improved safety by reducing the need for personnel in hazardous environments, cost efficiencies through faster data collection, and enhanced asset integrity management.

Mick Borwell, Environment Director at OEUK, played a pivotal role in this collaborative effort. Mr. Borwell highlighted that these new guidelines are essential for integrating UAS technology responsibly and effectively into daily offshore tasks. He emphasized that the primary goal is to ensure that while the industry embraces technological advancements, safety remains paramount. The comprehensive nature of these guidelines will enable operators to maximize the advantages of UAS while adhering to robust safety standards, fostering best practices, and ensuring regulatory compliance within the UK's offshore sector.

The animal welfare team on the council could be cut to such an extent it would only fulfil its statutory obligation to seize and kennel stray dogs. This stark proposal, set to be presented at the upcoming council meeting in February, has caused widespread alarm. Critics argue such cuts would severely impair the team's ability to proactively address animal cruelty, conduct welfare checks, or offer vital community education. Instead of focusing on broader animal well-being, the team would become a minimal reactive service, primarily dealing with a lost dog and immediate crises. This significant reduction in resources could ultimately lead to more animal suffering across the borough.

Kathryn Smith said she received ¬£52 a week in income support , some of which was used to buy the Class B substance . Jurors previously heard she was concerned 21 - month - old Ayeeshia Jane Smith may have had a seizure after taking drugs kept at the house . Ms Smith and ex - partner Matthew Rigby both deny murder . More on this and other stories from Stoke and Staffordshire The toddler , known as AJ , died in 2014 at the family home in St Giles Road, Burton-upon-Trent, following what the prosecution described as a "terrible assault". The court heard that AJ suffered "catastrophic" injuries, including a lacerated heart and internal bleeding, consistent with a severe impact. Post-mortem examinations revealed that Ayeeshia Jane Smith also had historic injuries, including a previous brain bleed and fractures to her ribs, consistent with her having been subjected to non-accidental harm on more than one occasion before her death.

Opening the prosecution's case, Christopher Hotten QC told the jury that both Ms Smith, 23, and Matthew Rigby, 21, were responsible for the fatal injuries inflicted upon AJ. He alleged that the couple, who were in a volatile relationship, had engaged in a "joint enterprise" to inflict serious harm, or that one had caused the injuries while the other failed to protect the child. The jury was presented with evidence of a chaotic household where drug use, including cannabis, was prevalent. Ms Smith's admission about using her limited income support to fund drug purchases underlined the difficult environment AJ was living in. The prosecution highlighted texts and calls between Ms Smith and Rigby in the hours leading up to AJ's death, which painted a picture of tension and concern about AJ's health, specifically the worry that she may have ingested drugs.

During cross-examination, Ms Smith maintained her innocence, accusing Matthew Rigby of being the one who inflicted the fatal injuries. She claimed she had briefly left the room and returned to find AJ unresponsive. Conversely, Rigby's defence team argued that it was Ms Smith who was responsible, suggesting she had a history of losing her temper and being violent. The court heard conflicting accounts from both defendants, each attempting to shift blame onto the other. Social services had been involved with the family prior to AJ's death, and concerns about the child's welfare had been raised on multiple occasions. Evidence presented included records of these interventions and assessments. The trial, presided over by Mr Justice Haddon-Cave at Stafford Crown Court, continues to hear from medical experts, police officers, and other witnesses who were involved in the investigation. The jury's task is to determine who was responsible for the tragic death of Ayeeshia Jane Smith, considering the complex web of evidence and conflicting narratives presented by the defence and prosecution. The deeply distressing nature of the case, involving a young child, has drawn significant public attention to the proceedings.

The four bedroom Georgian home provided the setting where eight - year - old Kevin McCallister , played by Macauley Culkin , outwitted a pair of bungling burglers . The film earned more than $ 477 m worldwide, equating to over ¬£291 million, solidifying its place as a holiday classic. The iconic Georgian residence, central to Kevin McCallister’s ingenious traps and escapades, was not custom-built for the movie but was a real family home located in Winnetka, Illinois. This distinctive property, instantly recognizable to fans, served as the primary set for many of Macauley Culkin’s memorable scenes as the resourceful young protagonist. For decades, the house has been owned by John and Cynthia Abendshien, who graciously allowed their private residence to be transformed into the McCallister family home for the duration of filming. They have often recounted stories of the filming process, particularly how the production team worked around their family life, even using parts of their home for crew facilities. The enduring appeal of the film continues to draw curious onlookers to the quiet suburban street, eager to catch a glimpse of the house where Kevin McCallister famously defended his turf against the Wet Bandits, forever linking the stately architecture with the timeless tale of a boy's unexpected holiday adventure.

Hank Costain, 88, from Charminster, near Dorchester, first flew a Spitfire in 1942, at the age of 19.
The maiden flight of the Supermarine Spitfire took place on 5 March 1936, from Eastleigh Aerodrome, now Southampton Airport.
Mr Costain described flying a Spitfire as "absolutely marvellous".
He said: "When you first got into the seat and opened the throttle it felt as if someone had given you a good kick up the bottom and away you went.
"It would do everything you asked of it. Compared to other aircraft it was light on the controls, you could do all the aerobatics and you would come up to speed very quickly.
"If you treated a Spitfire properly, it treated you properly. Treat it roughly or be careless with it and you were in trouble, in that it would do all sorts of things such as ground looping. It also had a very fragile undercarriage and could collapse."
Mr Costain was a member of the RAF for 37 years.
He flew operational Spitfires over Europe, north Africa, the Middle East and Burma.
He was also a Spitfire instructor during that time and became a test pilot on Spitfires at 9MU Cosford, Shropshire.
He said: "Everyone that joined the air force wanted to fly a Spitfire.
"I would say that I have flown nearly all of the operational Spitfires.
"There aren't many of us left [alive] that have flown the number of different marks of Spitfire that I have."
During and since his flying days, Mr Costain says he has often been asked if he was frightened during the war years.
He said: "I was terrified, but I was terrified of letting my own friends see that I was frightened. One made one's self very determined that you wouldn't show that.
"If you were attacked when you were flying a Spitfire during the war years, you turned hard into the attacking aircraft and they just couldn't get behind you! It was much more manoeuvrable than the German aircraft.
"I don't think we should ever forget what the Spitfire did for England. It was virtually England's saving grace."

As many as 23 civilians were killed in the raid on a village in Yakla district on Saturday , including 10 children , rights group Reprieve says . Yemeni reports say the victims included the daughter of Anwar al - Awlaki , a militant killed by a US strike in 2011 . The raid was the first such operation authorised by President Donald Trump . The US military had previously said a Navy Seal , William " Ryan " Owens , 36 , died and three others were wounded. The Pentagon asserted the operation targeted al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula (AQAP) and yielded significant intelligence, calling it a successful mission. However, these claims were swiftly countered by Yemeni officials and human rights organizations, who reported a much higher civilian death toll and questioned the mission's efficacy and planning.

Reprieve, a UK-based human rights group, stated that its ground investigators confirmed the deaths of at least 23 civilians, including 10 children, in the Yakla raid. Among the child victims was eight-year-old Nawar al-Awlaki, daughter of the American-Yemeni cleric Anwar al-Awlaki, who was himself killed in a US drone strike in 2011. Her family confirmed her death, sparking further outrage and highlighting the complex human cost of counter-terrorism operations in Yemen. Local reports indicated widespread destruction, with houses damaged and several civilians caught in the crossfire.

The high civilian casualty count and the death of a US serviceman immediately put the raid under intense scrutiny, particularly as it was the first authorized military action of President Trump's administration. Critics, including some US lawmakers, raised concerns about the intelligence used to approve the mission and its execution. Senator John McCain, then chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, initially described the mission as a "failure" due to the loss of life, though he later softened his stance. The US military launched an investigation into the civilian casualties amidst persistent questions about the tactical success and strategic implications of the operation in Yakla, al-Bayda province.

Rodriguez opened the scoring with a close - range header from Kieran Trippier 's cross after three minutes . Having missed a penalty , awarded for Garath McCleary 's foul on Ben Mee , Rodriguez then headed his second from another Trippier cross . On - loan Wolves man Adlene Guedioura went closest for the visitors, rattling the crossbar with a powerful long-range effort early in the second half. Despite their spirited efforts, Wolves struggled to find a way past Burnley's resolute defence, marshalled expertly by Ben Mee. The home side, buoyed by Rodriguez's brace, controlled much of the possession in the midfield, with Trippier continuing to be a menace down the right flank, his delivery a constant threat.

Burnley’s dominance was evident, and they continued to press for a third goal to put the game beyond doubt. Scott Arfield and George Boyd worked tirelessly on the wings, creating space for the full-backs to push forward. Trippier, in particular, seemed to be enjoying one of his most influential performances of the season, his crosses causing panic in the Wolves penalty area time and again. However, Wolves goalkeeper Carl Ikeme pulled off several key saves to deny Burnley further additions to the scoreline, including a superb stop from a fierce Rodriguez volley that would have completed his hat-trick.

As the game wore on, Wolves pushed higher, desperate to find a goal that would reignite their hopes. Garath McCleary, who had been involved in the early penalty incident, tried to make amends with some penetrating runs, but his efforts were largely isolated. Burnley’s backline, with Mee at its heart, stood firm against the late pressure. Manager Sean Dyche made tactical substitutions to shore up the midfield and defence, bringing on fresh legs to maintain their high work rate. The final whistle blew with Burnley securing a comfortable 2-0 victory, a result that reflected their superior attacking prowess and defensive solidity. Rodriguez's clinical finishing, combined with Kieran Trippier's exceptional service, proved to be the decisive factors in a commanding performance by the Clarets. The win saw Burnley climb further up the Championship table, consolidating their position as serious promotion contenders. Wolves, meanwhile, were left to ponder a missed opportunity on the road.

It is understood the Hammers will raise their offer for the player who began his career at the east London club . Defoe , 34 , has scored 11 goals in 21 appearances for the Premier League strugglers this season . His latest goals came on Monday as Sunderland twice fought from a goal deficit to draw 2-2 with Liverpool at the Stadium of Light. Despite their precarious Premier League position, Sunderland are resolute in their stance that Defoe is not for sale. West Ham's pursuit, however, remains persistent. Bringing a player of Defoe's calibre and Premier League experience back to the London Stadium is seen as a key move to bolster their ambitions. The reported increased offer from the east London club is said to be around £6 million, but Sunderland are understood to value him considerably higher, closer to £10-12 million, reflecting his irreplaceable status. Defoe himself has maintained focus on his on-field commitments, embodying dedication to the Black Cats. His current priority is unequivocally keeping Sunderland in the top flight, a monumental task he has largely spearheaded. This transfer saga is expected to continue until the window closes, with West Ham anticipated to test Sunderland's resolve further, even as the Black Cats stand firm on their 'not for sale' position regarding their talisman.

Senioli , a scrum - half for Italian side Treviso pointed and smiled at Scott Williams , who plays for Welsh team Scarlets , as he ran towards the line during a crucial game in Italy . It should have been an easy try , but the Wales international , known for his relentless defensive work and never-say-die attitude, launched himself forward with a desperate lunge. The stadium, filled with passionate Italian fans roaring for Treviso, held its breath as Williams, defying the odds, somehow managed to get a hand to Senioli's ankle just inches from the try-line. The Treviso player stumbled, his momentum broken, and the ball, which he had been cradling loosely in anticipation of the score, was dislodged. It bounced once, tantalisingly close to the whitewash, before a Scarlets forward, arriving belatedly but opportunistically, dived on it, securing the turnover. The collective groan from the Italian crowd was almost as loud as the roar of relief from the small contingent of travelling Welsh supporters. Senioli, still sprawled on the turf, looked up in disbelief, the earlier smile replaced by a grimace of frustration. Scott Williams, quickly back on his feet, simply nodded, a silent testament to the high stakes of this cross-border encounter. This single moment, a testament to Williams's grit, shifted the momentum. Treviso, who had been dominating, suddenly looked rattled, while Scarlets, buoyed by the miraculous defensive stop, found a new surge of energy. The game, critical for both sides' European aspirations, hung finely in the balance, a true showcase of the intensity of rugby between Italy and Wales.

Writing in the Journal of Aesthetic Nursing , clinicians say there is a growing trend for under-25s to seek the wrinkle - smoothing injections . But the research suggests " frozen faces " could stop young people from learning how to express emotions fully . A leading body of UK plastic surgeons says injecting teenagers for cosmetic reasons is " morally wrong " . Botox and other versions of the toxin work by temporarily paralysing muscles in the upper face to reduce wrinkling when people frown . Nurse practitioner Helen Collier , who carried out the research , says reality TV and social media are significant drivers behind this worrying trend. She observed that many young clients are influenced by the flawless, often filter-enhanced, appearances portrayed online and in popular culture, leading to unrealistic expectations about their own looks. Ms Collier, whose findings are detailed in the Journal of Aesthetic Nursing, expressed particular concern about the psychological implications of intervening with a developing brain's ability to express and interpret emotions. She explained that the muscles targeted by Botox are crucial not only for frowning but also for conveying a wide range of human emotions, from surprise to sadness. If these muscles are routinely paralysed from an early age, it could hinder a young person's capacity to fully experience and communicate their feelings, potentially impacting their social development and emotional intelligence.

The research highlighted that while older patients often seek Botox to reverse visible signs of aging, younger individuals are increasingly opting for "preventative Botox," hoping to stop wrinkles from forming in the first place. This shift in motivation raises profound ethical questions for practitioners. Ms Collier argues that genuine informed consent is difficult to obtain from teenagers, whose brains are still developing, and who may not fully grasp the long-term consequences of such procedures. She emphasized that the decision to undergo a cosmetic procedure like Botox should be made maturely, weighing the risks and benefits, something many under-25s are not yet equipped to do.

The British Association of Aesthetic Plastic Surgeons (BAAPS), a leading body of UK plastic surgeons, has echoed these concerns, reiterating its strong stance against cosmetic injections for those under 18, deeming it "morally wrong." Even for those slightly older but still under 25, BAAPS advises extreme caution and thorough psychological assessment before any treatment. They advocate for a focus on mental well-being and body positivity rather than promoting interventions that can have irreversible impacts on a young person's self-perception and emotional development.

Ms Collier's research, published in the Journal of Aesthetic Nursing, urges clinicians to prioritize the mental health and developmental needs of young patients. She calls for stricter regulations around the marketing and administration of cosmetic injectables to minors and young adults, suggesting that a mandatory cooling-off period and psychological evaluation should be standard practice. She believes that practitioners have a duty of care to protect vulnerable individuals from potential harm, and this includes resisting the commercial pressures to provide treatments that may not be in the patient's best interest. The findings underscore the urgent need for a societal shift away from the relentless pursuit of an artificial ideal of perfection towards embracing natural beauty and promoting healthy self-esteem among young people in the UK and globally. This involves educating both practitioners and the public about the true purpose and potential downsides of procedures like Botox, ensuring that informed decisions are made, and that the emotional and psychological well-being of young people remains paramount. The long-term effects of widespread Botox use in this age group on collective emotional literacy and non-verbal communication are yet unknown, adding another layer of concern for experts like Helen Collier.

Media playback is not supported on this device The 38 - year - old , making his Open debut , briefly led the Championship with his two under par score in tough conditions at Royal Birkdale . " I thought par would be a decent score on my first attempt , " a delighted Manley told BBC Radio Wales . Manley finished strongly with and eagle three on the par five 17th and a superb birdie four on the par-four 18th, completing a remarkable two-under-par round of 68. The Welshman, a relative unknown on the professional circuit and making his major championship debut, was visibly thrilled as he walked off the final green, acknowledging the cheers from the appreciative Royal Birkdale crowd. His impressive display, particularly his back-nine surge which saw him card three birdies and that crucial eagle, defied pre-tournament expectations in the notoriously challenging conditions.

Speaking further to BBC Radio Wales after his round, Manley reflected on the unexpected nature of his performance. "Honestly, I was just hoping to make the cut," he admitted with a grin. "To be up there on the leaderboard, even for a short while, is beyond anything I could have imagined. I've dreamt of playing in The Open my whole life, and to perform like this on the first day, at such an iconic venue like Royal Birkdale, it's just surreal. The course was brutal out there today with the wind and the rain coming in at times, so to post a score like that feels incredibly special."

His unexpected charge caught the attention of both seasoned golf commentators and the wider media. Suddenly, the focus wasn't just on the established stars, but on the plucky debutant who had briefly stolen the show. Manley’s humble demeanor and evident joy resonated with fans, who were quickly drawn to his underdog story. With three more rounds to play, the challenge of maintaining such form remained, but for one glorious day, the 38-year-old Welshman had announced his arrival on golf's biggest stage, setting a high bar for his own expectations and providing a compelling narrative for the championship.

Giuseppi Roncari 's body was discovered by officers in Blackburn Street , Salford at 19:20 BST on Monday . Detectives from Greater Manchester Police quickly launched a murder investigation into the death of the 42-year-old. Roncari, believed to have lived locally in Salford, was pronounced dead at the scene. A Home Office post-mortem examination will be carried out to determine the exact cause of Giuseppi Roncari's death. Police are appealing for anyone who saw anything suspicious in the area around that time BST to come forward.

The weapon was one of a pair of daggers discovered by British archaeologist Howard Carter in 1925 within the burial wrappings of the teenaged king . The origin of its unrusted iron blade has baffled scientists because such metalwork was rare in ancient Egypt . Tutankhamun was mummified more than 3,300 years ago . Italian and Egyptian researchers used " a non - invasive X - ray technique " to confirm that the iron blade was indeed of extraterrestrial origin, likely from a meteorite. The study, published in the journal Meteoritics and Planetary Science, analyzed the blade's elemental composition, revealing high levels of nickel and cobalt, elements typically found in iron meteorites but rare in terrestrial iron. This groundbreaking finding provided a definitive answer to a long-standing archaeological mystery that had puzzled experts since Howard Carter’s initial discovery of the dagger in Tutankhamun's tomb.

The sophisticated X-ray fluorescence analysis, conducted by researchers from the Polytechnic University of Milan and the Egyptian Museum in Cairo, eliminated any doubt about the blade's celestial source. The presence of nickel, in particular, was a key indicator, as iron extracted from ores on Earth rarely contains such high concentrations. This suggests that ancient Egyptian metallurgists, despite their advanced skills in working with gold and copper, utilized this unique, readily available raw material from the sky. The fact that the dagger has remained largely uncorroded for over three millennia further supports its meteoric origin, as meteoric iron is often more resistant to rust due to its unique crystalline structure and composition.

This discovery sheds new light on the technological capabilities and available resources in ancient Egypt during the New Kingdom period. It implies that the Egyptians were not only aware of falling 'sky-iron' but also possessed the skills to forge it into intricate objects of immense value, fit for a pharaoh like Tutankhamun. The cultural significance of such a material, literally descended from the heavens, would have been profound, adding to the mystique and power attributed to the young king. The other dagger found alongside it was made of gold, contrasting sharply with the 'celestial' iron one, highlighting the distinct and perhaps revered nature of the iron blade. This research emphasizes the interdisciplinary approach needed to unravel the secrets of ancient civilizations, combining archaeology, art history, and modern scientific analysis to provide unprecedented insights into the past of Tut and his people.

For the first time , MPs have agreed in a vote that we will begin the process of leaving the EU by the end of March . The government chief whip was seen with a massive grin after tonight 's vote . Remember ministers ' climbdown came with a clever kicker , persuading Labour to sign up to their timetable for triggering Article 50 without committing to very much in return The 'clever kicker' was the government’s commitment to publish a Brexit white paper and allow a parliamentary debate on the negotiating strategy before Article 50 is invoked. This strategic concession offered vital political cover for Labour MPs, particularly those representing pro-remain constituencies. It enabled them to vote for the timetable, framing their support as a push for parliamentary scrutiny rather than capitulation to Theresa May’s agenda. This allowed them to appease concerned constituents and avoid accusations of obstructing the democratic will.

For Theresa May, this parliamentary triumph is paramount. It solidifies her authority over the Brexit process, demonstrating her ability to command a Commons majority for her timeline. The chief whip’s satisfaction signalled successful navigation of perilous political currents, momentarily silencing critics. This outcome strengthens May’s hand for complex negotiations with the EU, reinforcing her narrative that the UK is united in its resolve to leave by the deadline. The focus now shifts decisively from the mechanism of triggering Article 50 to defining Britain's future relationship with Europe.

However, deep divisions persist. While Labour’s leadership found a pragmatic way through, many within the party and the broader remain camp remain uneasy. The white paper offers limited real parliamentary power over final Brexit terms. Pro-remain voices will undoubtedly intensify as the immense complexities of disentangling from the EU become clearer, especially regarding single market and customs union access. The coming months will severely test the government’s resolve and party cohesion as Brexit’s true impact unfolds. This vote merely concludes the first chapter, ushering in the far more challenging phase of withdrawal and negotiation.
